<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Extends 100 Million U.S. Dollar Aid to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA) extended 100 million U.S. dollars to support India's
population and development program Friday on the eve of the World
Population Day.
</P>
<P>
The amount, to be utilized for the integrated population and
development projects covering 40 districts in six states, is for a
five-year period (1997-2001), UNFPA representative in New Delhi
Wasim Zaman told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The aid is 30 percent higher than the 70 million U.S. dollars
provided to the populous country during the period of 1991 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
Joint Secretary in the Department of Family Welfare K. S.
Sugathan said at the press conference that 50 percent of the UNFPA
aid is for integrated population and development while the
remaining 50 percent would be used for national projects such as
strengthening logistic system for distribution of essential
medicines and contraceptives and implementing the national policy
for empowerment of women.
</P>
<P>
UNFPA also earmarked 10 million U.S. dollars for
non-governmental organizations and voluntary groups, Zaman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
