<HEADLINE> France, Britain Draft U.N. Resolution on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- France and Britain are to present a
draft resolution to the U.N. Security Council urging the two sides
in Kosovo to accept a ceasefire appeal from the Contact Group on
the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken the initiative with the United Kingdom to
prepare a draft resolution for the Security Council aimed at
implementing the declaration of the Contact Group in Bonn on July
8," said French Foreign Ministry assistant spokesman Yves
Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will discuss the resolution next week, and
France hoped it would be adopted rapidly, he said.
</P>
<P>
The six-nation Contact Group -- the United States, Britain,
France, Russia, Germany and Italy -- Wednesday called on the
Yugoslav government and Albanian rebels in Kosovo to cease
hostilities immediately and resume dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"It would recall, in a single text, the obligations which fall
upon the two sides -- ceasing actions of hostility to allow the
holding of dialogue, implementing all the commitments made by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Moscow on June 16, asking
Belgrade and Albanians of Kosovo to guarantee the security and
freedom of movement of the international observers working in
Kosovo," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
If the obligations were not respected by either side, the
Western countries would consider other measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Any further measures to be taken on Kosovo would need the
authorization of the Security Council, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
