<HEADLINE> Pentagon to Delay Lockheed Antimissile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon is delaying the
next test in its Theater High Altitude Area Defense System after
spending 3.2 billion U.S. dollars on five unsuccessful tests on a
system designed to shoot down missiles aimed at U.S. troops, the
Wall Street Journal said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon also said it was taking a series of steps to
restructure the program and effectively punish the prime
contractor Lockheed Martin Corp., which the Pentagon claims has
poorly managed the program.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, Lockheed is expected to pick up a
significant part of the multimillion-dollar costs of any future
tests that fail, said Air Force Lt. General Lester Lyles, head of
the Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, which oversees the
program.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Lockheed has offered to pay as much as 15
million dollars for each future test flight failure, although the
amount and other specific terms remain open to negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Because of the failures and changes in the program, the next
test flight which was originally planned in August may be
conducted this fall.
</P>
<P>
The United States planned to start the deployment of the
antimissile system in 2006 at a cost of 14 billion dollars, but
Lyles indicated the delivery date might be delayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
