<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Sergeant Alleged of Taking Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- An Air Force staff sergeant of
the U.S. military allegedly exploited weakness in defense
contracting procedures and paid himself about 1 million U.S.
dollars that was supposed to go to defense contractors, U.S. Air
Force investigation found.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has scheduled a general court-martial next week
for Staff Sergeant Robert L. Miller Jr., who is charged with
funding government money to himself through his girlfriend and
others, the Washington Post said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Miller is also accused of cheating defense contractors of
interest payments by the government.
</P>
<P>
In twin investigations, the Defense Criminal Investigative
Service and Air Force investigators last year researched checks
deposited in several banks. Investigators charged that Miller had
drawn up several U.S. Treasury checks made out to his civilian
girlfriend. She cashed the checks and sent the money back to
Miller.
</P>
<P>
Miller became chief of the Data Entry branch of the Dayton
Operating Location of the Defense Finance and Accounting Service
in 1995. He is accused of revising contractor's invoices to make
it look like his girlfriend or others he knew had done the work
and thus should receive the federal checks. It was unnoticed for
several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
