<HEADLINE> Canada's Housing Starts Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Housing construction in Canada fell
in June to its lowest level since September 1996, dragged down
mainly by labor disruptions in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
June is the third consecutive month of decline, 4.6 percent
down from May. A total of 132,700 units were recorded in June
across the country.
</P>
<P>
In Canada's largest city of Toronto, the rate of housing
construction hit its lowest level in five years.
</P>
<P>
If the work stoppages by the construction trades continue, the
July rate will fall even further, reports predicted.
</P>
<P>
A sharp decrease in new houses in the western provinces was
another factor pulling down the national rate.
</P>
<P>
The decline is causing some concern among economists. "The
situation bears some monitoring," one was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The housing market may represent only five percent of gross
domestic product, but it is often a very reliable leading
indicator of overall economic activity," the economist noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
