<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Price Difference Remains High in E.U. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain is the most expensive
place to buy a new car in the European Union where prices can vary
by up to 60 percent for one model, a European Commission report
revealed Friday.
</P>
<P>
A comparison of price differences between neighboring countries
with sufficiently homogeneous market conditions revealed
substantial divergences and found no significant changes since the
previous report last November.
</P>
<P>
The Ford Mondeo, for example, recorded a 58.5 percent
difference between the highest and lowest prices in May among the
15 EU members, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report, the 11th of its type, claimed that 60 of the 74
best-selling models examined by the EU executive arm were dearest
in Britain while the lowest prices for 34 models were found in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Spain and Portugal were the cheapest countries for 14 of the
models.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Rating, spokesman for the commission's competition
commissioner, said the report would help potential buyers to
decide where to purchase cars.
</P>
<P>
The difference of car prices was explained by the argument that
list prices in individual member states are determined by general
market conditions and that manufacturers take into account the
taxes linked to car purchases.
</P>
<P>
In Britain, France and Germany which have no sale-linked taxes,
pre-tax prices tend to be set higher by manufacturers, while they
are usually set lower in countries with such taxes, said the
commission officials.
</P>
<P>
Non-resident buyers acquiring a car for immediate re-export do
not have to pay such taxes with the purchase.
</P>
<P>
The report for May listed the smallest difference at 12 percent
for the BMW318i.
</P>
<P>
Six months earlier in a previous commission report, the biggest
difference in car prices was reported at 54.3 percent for the VW
Polo and the smallest difference of 12.5 percent for Audi A4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Presents New Budget in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Finance Minister Ram
Saran Mahat Friday presented to parliament a budget which shows an
increase both in development and regular expenditures for the
1998/99 fiscal year that begins in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Of the 69.693 billion rupees (1.1 billion U.S. dollars) budget
estimate presented to the joint sitting of the bicameral
parliament, 37.741 billion rupees (570 million dollars) are
earmarked for development expenditure and 31.952 billion rupees
(480 million dollars) for regular expenditure, up 25.7 percent and
15.4 percent respectively over those of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
On the sources of the budget, Mahat said that 39.479 billion
rupees (600 million dollars) will be borne from the revenue
resources and 7.772 billion rupees (120 million dollars) will be
met by foreign bilateral and multilateral grant assistance.
</P>
<P>
The deficit of 22.442 billion rupees (340 million dollars) will
be met by foreign bilateral and multilateral loans and internal
loans from the banking and other sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation of deficit budget has been besetting Nepal for
years and the deficit is increasing every year.
</P>
<P>
Mahat said that the government has decided to mobilize
government revenues and increase productivity of government
investment with a view to bringing about changes in public
finances.
</P>
<P>
And the government has also decided to extend public sector
investment, strengthen the financial sectors, increase financial
activities and direct the government efforts toward agriculture,
the rural areas, human development, poverty alleviation,
employment generation and social welfare, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mahat said in May that his biggest challenge ahead was the
budget. And for the minority government led by Girija Prasad
Koirala, the budget is truly crucial for its survival.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), which supported the government when it
came to power in mid-April, Thursday voted against the programs
and policies presented by the government for the coming fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The programs and polices were passed in parliament Thursday.
</P>
<P>
For the passage of the new budget in the 205-seat Lower House
of Parliament, a simple majority of 103 votes is need.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Nepali Congress (NC) has only 88 seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post daily said that the NC has reached
understanding with the CPN-ML that the latter will be inducted
into the government after the passage of the budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
