<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Mayor Put Under House Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Mayor of Uganda's capital city of
Kampala Nasser Sebaggala has been put under house arrest by a
federal judge in Boston, the United States, pending trial on bank
fraud charges on a date yet to be set.
</P>
<P>
This decision dashed hopes that Sebaggala would be allowed to
return home before trial.
</P>
<P>
During a detention hearing Thursday, U.S. Magistrate Judge
Marianne Bowler placed Sebaggala under the custody of Edmund
Narine, a Boston resident, the New Vision daily said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The judge said the mayor will have to remain at Narine's house
until his trial. He can only leave the premises under "emergency
situation."
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was also made to deposit a cash bond of 50,000 U.S.
Dollars and an unsecured bond of 950,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
His defense lawyers said that they plan to appeal the judge's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Paul Kelly, one of the two defense attorneys, told journalists
outside the court that "I am neither satisfied nor pleased with
the verdict... nevertheless, I respect the judge's decision."
</P>
<P>
"We will definitely appeal the judge's decision and we will
ask the district judge to review the conditions and allow Mr.
Sebaggala to return to Kampala and perform his duties as Mayor,"
said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala, however, told his Kampala supporters in a call
Thursday that he is innocent and confident that he will return
home any time.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was arrested on June 13 in New York for allegedly
making false customs declaration and depositing altered checks in
a U.S. bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
