<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Pledges to Form Economic Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen pledged Friday to form an "economic government"
if the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) wins the election.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he said, he would peacefully hand over the power
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks after meeting visiting Thai army chief
General Chettha Thanajaro at his Takhmau residence in Kandal, 12
kilometers south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Chettha Thanajaro, who will retire at the end of September,
arrived here Friday on a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
When asked about what preparations he had made for the upcoming
elections, Hun Sen said he was ready for everything.
</P>
<P>
First, he said, he would ensure the elections were held without
violence. Secondly, he was prepared to solve economic problems,
such as the drought and food shortages that Cambodian people are
facing.
</P>
<P>
As for the elections, he said he had made two preparations. If
the CPP won, he would form an "economic government". If it lost,
he would hand over power peacefully and immediately warmly
congratulate the winning party.
</P>
<P>
"Economic problems will be a top priority, if I become prime
minister of the next government", Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen estimated that the CPP would win about six out of 11
Assembly seats in Kandal where he will compete as CPP's
candidate. But even if the CPP got only one seat, he would not
give up.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, he had estimated that the CPP would altogether win
about 45 to 60 percent of the 122 National Assembly seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that as a prime minister, he would do his
best to ensure a free, fair and credible atmosphere for the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also disclosed that the investigations on the victims
of last July's events, including the grenade attack before the
National Assembly on March 30 last year had made some
progress. But action would be taken after the election.
</P>
<P>
People would be surprised by the outcome of the investigation
when it was made public, Hun Sen added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
