<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Promises to Seek Release of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri said on Friday that his government would make every effort
to seek the release of all Lebanese prisoners held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the remarks during a meeting with representatives
of the Lebanese prisoners recently set free by Israel and their
supporters, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the government would take effective measures
to help the freed reintegrate into the society and provide them
with a decent life.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by the International Committee of the Red Cross,
Israel released 60 Lebanese prisoners and returned the bodies of
40 Lebanese guerrillas last month in exchange for the remains of
an Israeli soldier killed in south Lebanon last year.
</P>
<P>
But Israel is still detaining another 117 Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Israel allowed 43 Lebanese to visit their
relatives jailed in Khiam prison in south Lebanon for the first
time in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
The prison, established by Israeli army and run by its ally
South Lebanese Army, is used to hold those who join the
anti-Israeli guerrilla group Hezbollah (Party of God) and people
who refuse to collaborate with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese resistance forces, which have
been fighting to oust the Israeli troops. 
</P>
