<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Construction of Kalabagh Dam Causes Mighty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The government of Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has set off a vigorous campaign at state-run
electronic media to build up public opinion in favor of a
controversial dam on river Indus which is vehemently opposed by
regional and nationalist parties.
</P>
<P>
"Kalabagh dam will improve Indus Water system and bring
economic prosperity by raising hydro-energy and improving
irrigation system," Shamsul Mulk, chairman of the state-run Water
and Power Development Authority (WABDA), said in a recent debate
on Pakistan Television.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif announced construction of the dam on June
11 as part of the national agenda aimed at making energy-starved
Pakistan a self-reliant nation following the economic sanctions by
some Western countries triggered by Pakistan's detonation of
nuclear devices 17 days after similar blasts by India in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said in a recent televised address to the
nation, "Construction of the Kalabagh dam will dawn a new era of
development by bringing green revolution in the country."
</P>
<P>
The government is of the view that the dam to be built at
Kalabagh in central Punjab province would help cultivate more than
one million acres (404,858 hectares) of land and generate
much-needed 3,600 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
However, the government's announcement has triggered strong
protests from the opposition and regional parties in three smaller
provinces--Sindh, North Western Frontier Province (NWFP) and
Balochistan.
</P>
<P>
The state legislatures of the three provinces have passed
unanimous resolutions rejecting the project and crippling strike
was observed in Sindh on June 17 to protest the government's
decision to go ahead with the hefty scheme.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition leader and former prime minister, Benazir
Bhutto, described the announcement as ill-timed, saying that "it
is a wrong decision at a wrong time as announcement was made
without taking into confidence the people of all the provinces."
</P>
<P>
The pro-dam lobby, however, argues that construction of
Kalabagh dam would help Pakistan save 2.4 billion U.S. dollars it
spends annually on oil imports the bulk of which is used for the
generation of electricity.
</P>
<P>
"Energy experts suggest the best possible way for the country
to meet its increasing energy demands would be to utilize its
water resources and construct huge water reservoirs not only for
electricity generation but also for irrigation purposes," said an
article in leading English daily The Nation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the dam when built would not only be highly
beneficial to the economy of the country as a whole but would also
bring a lot of prosperity to the people of the three provinces,"
The Nation said editorially.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an article carried by another major English daily
The Dawn said the Sindh and NWFP were convinced that construction
of Kalabagh dam would deprive them of their shares of water from
the river Indus.
</P>
<P>
The NWFP politicians feared that the province would not only
lose a big chunk of age-old villages and towns but large tracts of
fertile lands in Nowshera, Swabi and Mardan districts, rated as
most fertile land, due to submerging by flood waters.
</P>
<P>
The government's announcement of the construction of the
controversial dam has also sparked a heated debate in the recent
separate sessions of the National Assembly and Senate of the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Awami National Party (ANP), a major ethnic Pushtoon group
in NWFP which parted ways with the Sharif government early this
year over the renaming of the province, has threatened to start a
mass campaign against the construction of the dam.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to resist the Kalabagh dam tooth and nail," said
Senator Ajmal Khattack, president of ANP.
</P>
<P>
Asfandyar Wali, an ANP deputy in the National Assembly, urged
the government not to start work on the project without evolving
consensus of all the provinces.
</P>
<P>
Even some coalition partners of the ruling Pakistan Muslim
League (N) have opposed the construction of the dam without
national consensus.
</P>
<P>
Motahidda Qaumi Movement (MQM), the dominant political force in
urban Sindh and major component of the provincial coalition
government, has urged Prime Minister Sharif to take smaller
provinces into confidence over the issue.
</P>
<P>
the ruling Balochistan National Party in the southwestern
province has criticized the central government for what it said
ignoring view points of smaller provinces.
</P>
<P>
The government, on its part, says it would try to evolve
national consensus before starting construction work on the highly
explosive project. "We will address the reservation of the smaller
provinces," Sharif said following strong protests by the regional
and nationalist groups.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the dam would be equally beneficial for
the smaller provinces but regretted that a technical issue has
been turned into a political one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
