<HEADLINE> No Loans for Japan, South Korea: Blatter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- FIFA President Sepp Blatter said here on
Friday that the soccer's governing body would not consider giving
loans to Japan and South Korea, co-hosts of 2002 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Blatter also said that World Cup will be opened in Seoul of South
Korea on July 13, 2002 but the final will be held in a Japanese city.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think FIFA would accept such a demand to give a loan for
the organization of the World Cup," he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
He said FIFA has not received any reports from the two countries
that there have been problems in construction of venues and other
necessary infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
However, FIFA will send a specialists group this fall to inspect
the preparation for the World Cup, which will in turn report to an
Executive Committee meeting in December.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said in the group phase at the 2002 World Cup, 16 teams
will be competing in Japan while the other in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the two host countries will qualify for the
finals automatically, along with the defending champions.
</P>
<P>
But FIFA has yet to decide how the other 29 teams would qualify for
the finals and especially the allocation of slots among the
continental confederations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
