<HEADLINE> Pak PM Urges Nation to Prepare for Economic Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said here Friday the nation has to prepare itself for
sacrifices to meet the impact of sanctions as a price for
Pakistan's security.
</P>
<P>
Presiding over a high-level meeting with the heads of
nationalized commercial banks and business leaders at the Prime
Minister House, he said the government would give every facility
to industrialists and exporters in order to revive the country's
industry and expand and enhance exports on a massive scale.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also considered at length the problem of defaulted
loans of banks along with the overdue utility bills of certain
individuals and organizations, according to the Associated Press
of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
It was urged that stern action should be initiated against all
major defaulters by confiscating their properties and putting them
on auction.
</P>
<P>
Buyers of such properties will be given protection from probe
or question relating to sources of their income.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also directed the heads of banks and other financial
institutions to prepare a list of those bankers who were
instrumental in sanctioning such defaulted loans without adequate
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Pakistan was asked to prepare bankwise
targets for monthly recoveries of defaulted loans.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said high priority is being accorded to the revival of
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, also attended by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz and
Minister of Petroleum and Natural Resources Nisar Ali Khan,
considered a number of proposals in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
