<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Improve Aviation Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- African nations should resolve the
need for aviation safety for them to benefit from increased
economic growth, U.S. Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said aviation was the key to economic development in any
nation as nearly half of all world commerce was conducted by air.
</P>
<P>
He was giving a keynote address at the opening of a regional
meeting on the African safe skies initiative.
</P>
<P>
"To take full advantage of expanding air services and trade,"
Slater said, "African nations must first address safety and
security."
</P>
<P>
"I believe that aviation will play a major role in Africa's
future. It will help grow national economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Slater is on a mission to examine Africa's transportation
challenges and find ways the U.S. might help in the safe skies
initiative launched recently by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The initiative aims to improve aviation safety and security in
Africa in a bid to foster growth in aviation services between the
continent and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The initiative would complement United States' efforts to
conclude "open skies" agreements with key African countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being attended by transport ministers from
Angola, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Namibia, Swaziland, Tanzania,
Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Slater urged African countries to bring their aviation systems
in line with international civil aviation organization standards.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Transport and Energy Minister Enos Chikowore told
the meeting his government had a program aimed at strengthening
safety in the department of civil aviation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this is a bold move that should see our skies
becoming safer," he said, adding: "we look forward to cooperating
with your aviation administration to consolidate the work we have
started."
</P>
<P>
He hoped local airlines would be allowed into the U.S.
airspace since their airlines had been accorded similar status in
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
