<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN, C'wealth Chiefs Used by Nigerian Military: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Punch, a leading Nigerian paper
Friday said Chief Moshood Abiola, the opposition leader who died
in detention Tuesday, claimed that the military government had
used international figures for its own purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to a front-page story, which bears a by-line as "Our
Reporter", Abiola, the presumable winner of the June 12, 1993
presidential elections, suspected that United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and his Commonwealth counterpart
Emeka Anyaoku were working for the current military government to
ask him to renounce his mandate of the self-declared president.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, I believe the Federal Military Government 'used' the
two men to fly their kite on 'declaration' which was the main
issue they both said worried the Federal Military Government,"
Abiola said in his own account of the meetings between him and
the two persons last week.
</P>
<P>
The paper said this is Abiola's last but undated letter routed
through his wives to a pro-democracy group.
</P>
<P>
It also carries a full-page of photocopy of Abiola's original
handwriting, along with the full text of the transcript.
</P>
<P>
Annan said before the end of his visit that Abiola had agreed
to renounce his mandate following four years in detention.
</P>
<P>
"What i know is that I would want to get on with my life and I
also suspect that the world has moved on. And I cannot sit here
to be naive enough to make assumption that I'm going to be
president," Annan quoted Abiola as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, giving his own version of his meeting with the two
diplomats, Abiola wrote: "the two of them were working as agents
of the Federal Military Government whether they are paid or not."
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the late businessman politician denied that he
had agreed to renounce his mandate.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing on June 12 has been done 'under table' or at a
'secret meeting'... Giving a private 'declaration' to secure my
own release will make all concerned look cheap," according to the
letter.
</P>
<P>
Abiola also said he did not believe Annan's claims that nobody
in the international community will recognize him on the basis of
a five-year old mandate.
</P>
<P>
Virtually the same thing was discussed between Abiola and
Anyaoku, according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
Abiola also warned the unnamed addressee: "Beware how you use
this and other materials with you so as not to put the boys in
trouble" and he asked for a "Publicity Blitz" based on "all the
materials you have."
</P>
<P>
It has been noted that after Annan and Anyaoku's visit, the
reported renouncement by Abiola of his presidential mandate seems
to be a score the military government has gained and would be
helpful in a smooth political transition in the most populous
African country.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition and Abiola's supporters are suspicious
of the renouncement, which they feel like a loss in the struggle
between the Yoruba people in the southwest and the Hausa people
in the north.
</P>
<P>
Yoruba and Hausa are the two biggest ethnic groups in Nigeria.
Many senior military officers are from the Hausa group.
</P>
<P>
The sudden death of Abiola Tuesday afternoon increased the
suspicion that the military rulers have not treated Abiola well.
</P>
<P>
The supporters who disbelieved the government statement that
Abiola died of "cardiac arrest" took to the streets in major
southwestern cities for demonstration, during which riots have
killed more than 30 people.
</P>
<P>
As tension remains high in the southwest despite an uneasy
calm, the letter is expected to come as an igniter to some
radical opposition members and supporters who have vowed to expel
the northerners from power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
