<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 ICRC Aid Workers Set Free in Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Somali fundamentalist group
Friday announced the release of the six International Commission
of Red Cross (ICRC) aid workers kidnaped in the fifth zone of
Ethiopia on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Islamic fundamentalist group of
Al-Itihad Al-Islam in Ogaden region, Ibrahim Sheikh Omar, said
here that the aid workers were released Friday from their place
of captivity in Nogob region at 14:00 local time.
</P>
<P>
They are still on their way to a designated place where they
would be turned over to Somali elders and intellectuals in the
fifth zone as they put it, Omar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the ICRC officials in Ethiopia are notified of the
release Friday and they are coming on the designated spot which
he did not specify for "security reasons".
</P>
<P>
Omar said the aid workers were released despite their guilty
status proven on them during the 15-day investigations.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the ICRC aid workers were found
guilty in conducting businesses out of their duties, including
the transportation of money and fuel to the government workers in
the fifth zone of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the release of the ICRC workers is unconditional and
motivated purely on humanitarian ground.
</P>
<P>
Al-Itihad also said that the ICRC workers were treated well
during their captivity.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the only condition set for the release of
the aid workers was that they should notify of their movements in
the region to the Al-Itihad officials in the fifth zone
beforehand when "their Mujahidins operate against the occupation
forces."
</P>
<P>
Omar has accused Ethiopia of destabilizing the region. He
appealed for a referendum for the people of the fifth zone for
total independence from the rest of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reports reaching here indicate that the
humanitarian and health situation of the two French nationals
kidnaped by Somali militiamen in the northeastern coast last
month is getting better.
</P>
<P>
According to the elders who paid them a visit in Buro village,
45 km east of the port town of Bossaso, the hostages were allowed
to read books and are relatively well fed.
</P>
<P>
The elders also said that the French men were offered to make
phone calls to their relatives in France who reportedly
encouraged them to stop their fasting while the French government
was making diplomatic efforts to secure their release.
</P>
<P>
However, the abductors have now further increased their demand
of the ransom up to 85,000 U.S. Dollars. The kidnaped French men
were tourists on a small yacht on their way to Reunion island
controlled by France near Madagascar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
