<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tamoxifen Does Not Prevent Breast Cancer, Studies Suggest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- British and Italian researchers
said Friday that the anti-oestrogen drug tamoxifen did not appear
to prevent breast cancer in their studies.
</P>
<P>
The findings, published in the British medical journal The
Lancet, suggest that more trials will be needed before tamoxifen
can be routinely recommended for the prevention of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
Longer follow-up of these trials will be needed to assess the
impact of tamoxifen on breast-cancer death rates, the researchers
said.
</P>
<P>
The first trial, led by Dr Trevor Powles from the Royal Marsden
Hospital, of London, the UK, involved 2,494 women with a family
history of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
After a median follow-up of 70 months, researchers reported
that "the overall frequency of breast cancer is the same for women
on tamoxifen or placebo."
</P>
<P>
In the second study, Dr Umberto Veronesi and colleagues from
Milan and Bologna, Italy, randomly assigned 5,408 women who had
hysterectomies and also found "no difference in breast-cancer
frequency between the placebo and tamoxifen."
</P>
<P>
Commented in The Lancet, Professor Kathleen Pritchard from
Toronto, Canada, said that the new results "cast doubt on the
wisdom of the rush, at least in some places, to prescribe
tamoxifen widely for prevention." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
