<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Saudi United Bank (SUB) has achieved 78.7
million U.S. dollars in net profits and 241.6 million dollars in
operational profits during the first half of 1998, Kuwait News
Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the bank said that most of its financial
items have soared tremendously due to the merger of the Saudi
United Commercial Bank and the Saudi Cairo Bank into the Saudi
United Bank in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the growth in the bank's assets during the
first half of this year stood at 20.7 billion dollars compared
with 4.2 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The shareholders' rights in the bank have jumped to 1.1 billion
dollars from only 630 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SUB is the third largest bank in Saudi Arabia with an estimated
capital of 820 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi government would buy 21,000 tonnes of dates
worth 19.7 million dollars from farmers in the current season, the
Arabic-language Al-Hayat daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Minister of Agriculture and Water Abdullah Bin Abdul-Aziz
Bin Moammar told the daily that the move was aimed at promoting the
agricultural sector, "one of the major pillars of the national
economy."
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's representative at the World Bank Mohamed Kamel
Amr said on Friday that Egypt still needs foreign loans to sustain
economic development despite its efforts to reduce reliance on
them, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is carrying out 14 projects in Egypt's health,
irrigation, agriculture and port sectors, which are among the most
successful funded by the institution in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Terming the projects as "satisfactory and above-satisfactory,"
the Egyptian economist said the bank was ready to finance projects
in Egypt, such as the mammoth Toshka land reclamation project and
other new projects involving the protection of environment and
cultural heritage. 
</P>
