<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Reports 1st Outbreak of Mussel Poisoning in 30 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- British doctors reported Friday in
The Lancet medical journal the first outbreak of shellfish food
poisoning from mussels harvested in Britain in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to The Lancet, investigators from the UK's Central
Public Health Laboratory said that in June 1997, 49 patients
developed acute nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, abdominal pain and
fever within 30 minutes of eating mussels at two London
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
The symptoms lasted longer than eight hours in most of the
patients. The investigators tested samples of mussels from both
restaurants and found high concentration of a phycotoxin called
okadaic acid.
</P>
<P>
Phycotoxins are produced by small marine organisms. When they
are eaten by shellfish such as mussels, the concentrations are
very high and cause severe stomach problems in humans. Okadaic
acid is one of the most common shellfish toxins.
</P>
<P>
The recent outbreak in London is important, the investigators
said, because it "represents the first incident for 30 years
caused by phycotoxin contamination of UK shellfish and the first
ever incident having okadaic acid as the causative agent."
</P>
</TEXT>
