<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief Visits Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Chief of Staff Ismail
Hakki Karadayi visited the Turkish-controlled northern Cyprus
Friday amid rising tension on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from northern Cyprus said that Karadayi
promised that the Turkish army would guarantee the security of the
Turkish Cypriots living in the north.
</P>
<P>
In statements made upon his arrival, Karadayi said "the Turkish
Cypriots should not be nervous about the recent arms build-up by
the Greek Cypriots."
</P>
<P>
He described as a "provocation" the Cyprus government's
decision last year to purchase the S-300 anti-aircraft missile
system from Russia, adding that necessary measures were being
taken against Cyprus' planned deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating his country's willingness to keep peace on the
island, the Turkish general warned that Ankara is closely
monitoring every move taken by the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, one of three guarantor powers under the 1960 Treaty of
the establishment of the Cyprus Republic, has kept a
35,000-strong armed forces in northern Cyprus. Other two guarantor
powers are Greece and Britain.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day stay in the north, Karadayi inspected the
Turkish forces and discussed with Turkish Cypriot leaders counter
measures against the deployment of the missiles by the Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Karadayi's visit came amid the rising tension on this eastern
Mediterranean island where a tit-for-tat show of force took place
last month between Greece and Turkey by sending their warplanes on
the opposite sides of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou and Commander of the
Greek Cypriot National Guard Demetris Demou, who are currently
visiting Russia, watched Thursday a test firing of the S-300
missile, which is due to be delivered in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
But the Cyprus government has reportedly proposed a delay in
delivering the missiles until November this year in order to give
more time to allow the international mediators to achieve progress
toward a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has made it clear that it would halt the
deployment of the Russian-made missiles only if progress is made
on formulating a schedule for the island's demilitarization or in
the Cyprus peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has described Karadayi's trip to Cyprus' northern areas
as "illegal," saying will make representations to the United
Nations over the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
