<HEADLINE> UNFPA Calls for Concern Over World's Poor People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Population Fund
(UNFPA) said here Friday that the world's major concern should
not be rapid population growth rates but the millions of people
who are impoverished both materially and spiritually.
</P>
<P>
UNFPA Executive Director Nafis Sadik said in a statement
issued on the eve of the World Population Day that if the
individual reproductive health needs are taken care of, the
global need for slower and more balanced population growth will
take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
There are 1.165 billion people between the age of 15 and 24
and there are more 60-plus year olds living today than ever
before in the world, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Sadik said the eventual size of the world population will
depend on choices of people over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Young people need information and access to health care if
they are to make proper choices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's World Population Day is "approaching
the world of six billion."
</P>
<P>
The world population now standing at 5.9 billion is expected
to reach six billion in 1999, he noted. 
