<HEADLINE> Kenya to Benefit from Airline Alliance With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States Department of
Transportation Friday approved a code-sharing alliance between
Northwest Airlines and Kenya Airways.
</P>
<P>
"With this new alliance, passengers traveling between the U.S.
and Kenya can look forward to better and more convenient
service," U.S. Secretary for Transportation Rodney Slater said
here.
</P>
<P>
Slater was attending a conference of eastern and southern
African countries to discuss U.S. President Bill Clinton's Safe
Skies for Africa Initiative aimed at promoting sustainable
improvements in aviation safety and security on the continent.
</P>
<P>
He said the alliance supports the initiative also designed to
promote expanded aviation services between Africa and the U.S.,
which is considered critical to the world's poorest continent's
integration into the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The code-sharing alliance will enable Northwest Airlines to
place its code on flights operated by Kenya Airways between
Amsterdam of the Netherlands, Nairobi and beyond.
</P>
<P>
It is the second code-sharing arrangement between a U.S.
airline and an African airline.
</P>
<P>
American airlines and South African Airways have been
operating code-sharing service since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
