<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkeys Says No Bargaining on Cyprus Missile Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey declared Friday that it will
not accept any bargaining on the planned deployment of Russian
missiles by the Cyprus government.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli told a news
conference here that Turkey believed that the deployment of Russian
missiles was "a very dangerous development."
</P>
<P>
He was responding to Greece's suggestion that a no-fly zone be
established over Cyprus in return for the cancellation of the
deployment of the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in the
Creek Cypriots-controlled south.
</P>
<P>
"The solution of this problem is not up to us since we are not
the ones who created it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on a statement by Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz
that Turkey would also install missiles on the island, Atacanli
reiterated that Turkey was taking all necessary counter measures
against the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview late Thursday evening, Yilmaz
reaffirmed Turkey's determination not to make concessions over
the Cyprus dispute.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that if the S-300 missiles were deployed in
Cyprus, Turkey would respond by stepping up its military presence
to protect the Turkish Cypriots on the island.
</P>
<P>
"We will take all the necessary measures. If they bring
missiles, we will bring missiles too. If they install the
missiles in the south, we will increase our strength in the
north," Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, Cyprus signed a deal with Russia to buy the
S-300 missiles, triggering tensions on the small island. Turkey
has vowed to use all means to block the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
response to a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been providing political, economic and military
support to the Turkish Cypriots and is the sole country to
recognize the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was
unilaterally declared by the Turkish Cypriots in 1983.
</P>
<P>
At present, Turkey is stationing about 35,000 troops in
northern Cyprus with the claimed aim of protecting the Turkish
Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
