<HEADLINE> Koplan to Head Center for Disease Control and Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Jeffrey Koplan, a former
"disease detective" who specializes in cancer and the hazards of
smoking, was named Friday to head the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention (CDC) based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Koplan, who takes over in October, worked for 22 years with the
CDC and the former U.S. Public Health Service before leaving in
1994 to head the Prudential Center for Health Care Research in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala made the
announcement, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
He succeeds Dr. David Satcher, who was sworn in as U.S. surgeon
general in February.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old Koplan began his CDC career as an epidemic
intelligence service office. He also served as assistant to the
U.S. surgeon general and as the first director of the CDC's
National Center of Chronic Disease Prevention and Health
Promotion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
