<HEADLINE> N. Irish Orangemen Agrees to Talk with Catholic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Ireland's Protestant
Orangemen taking part in the stand-off with police agreed Friday
evening to participate in talks offered by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order has been banned from marching along the
Garvaghy Road in Portadown for fear of derailing last April's Good
Friday peace accord. The stand-off continued since last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Friday proposed "immediate
and indirect contact talks" to try to resolve the Drumcree
stand-off which has brought Northern Ireland to the brink of
chaos.
</P>
<P>
BBC reported that the Orange Order leaders had been positive to
take part in the meeting to be held in Northern Ireland Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, the Orange Order had refused to negotiate with the
residents' association on the grounds that its leader is linked to
the political wing of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
The other side, the Catholic Garvaghy Road residents'
association, which has been opposed to the Orangemen parade, also
responded positively to the talks initiative.
</P>
<P>
Breandan MacCionnaith, leader of the Garvaghy Road residents,
indicated that he was likely to attend the talks, to which he gave
"a cautious welcome".
</P>
<P>
But he told reporters he viewed proximity talks only as a first
step towards face-to-face talks with the Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the main Protestant political party,
the Ulster Unionists, and now first minister of the British
province's newly elected assembly, also welcomed talks proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I very much welcome this initiative," he told reporters in
Belfast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
