<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safe Skies Policy Supported by African Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States and seven
African countries Friday signed a declaration which calls for the
development and maintenance of safe and efficient transportation
systems under the Safe Skies Initiative.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, signed here by U.S. Secretary of
Transportation Rodney Slater and transport ministers from Angola,
Kenya, Malawi, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda and Zimbabwe, recognizes
the important role of transportation in the economic and social
well-being of each country.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers favored improving regional transportation
systems through strategic investment in transportation
infrastructure elements," said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed that safe air travel and secure
airport facilities are prerequisites for Africa's integration
into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Safe skies are necessary for increasing trade, attracting
investment, encouraging tourism and weaving together an
integrated regional society, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
"Recognizing the importance of safe and secure airports to
Africa's development, the ministers expressed their intention to
help marshal the political will and long-term resource commitment
necessary to meet safe skies goals," it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, the U.S. would help identify
internal sources of revenue which would make programs
self-funding through air traffic control, landing and airport
service fees.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the U.S. intends to provide short-term technical
advice and financial support in cooperation with regional
institutions, international financial institutions and
international civil aviation organizations," the declaration
said.
</P>
<P>
The Safe Skies Initiative, launched by U.S. President Bill
Clinton during his historic trip to Africa early this year, is
aimed at promoting sustainable improvements in aviation safety
and security in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
