<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Israel, Palestinians to Hold Direct Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Friday urged the Israeli and Palestinians to
take direct talks with each other, saying that this is the way to
solve remaining difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think that this impasse can be resolved ... if they
do not talk with each other ... It is essential that the parties
talk with each other," Albright told a news conference before a
meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the United States had been working hard to
refine American peace proposals and to narrow gaps between
Israel and the Palestinians, but "there is a limited amount that
the United States or anyone can do if the parties themselves do
not talk with each other to resolve the remaining difficult
issues."
</P>
<P>
Asked how long the U.S. effort would continue, Albright said:
"I believe that while there are constructive discussions going
on that it is worth continuing the process."
</P>
<P>
But "we are clearly coming to the end of this phase and we
cannot let it go on indefinitely," she warned.
</P>
<P>
This week, the United States has been intensifying its effort
to press Israel and the Palestinians for talks so that the
16-month deadlock could be broken up and the peace process
could be revitalized.
</P>
<P>
Albright herself spoke to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu seven times through telephone to urge him to accept a
U.S. proposal on Israel's further withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
She also met with a Palestinian delegation on Thursday after
talking with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on telephone on
Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
