<HEADLINE> Ahern Welcomes UK Initiative on Ending Ulster Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
Friday welcomed the British initiative on ending the impasse over
a banned Protestant march in Northern Ireland, according to press
reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair proposed early Friday that
representatives from the pro-British Orange Order and local Roman
Catholic residents hold indirect talks to bridge their
differences.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, a major player in the Northern Ireland peace process,
said in a statement issued in Dublin: "I would urge both the
Garvaghy Road residents and the Orange Order to cooperate fully
with this initiative."
</P>
<P>
"The preservation of peace must be everyone's priority. The
disorder and lawlessness that we have seen this week is very
damaging to the interests of Northern Ireland," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
The banning of the traditional annual Orange Order march in the
Catholic areas in Belfast has triggered wide-spread violence in
Northern Ireland over the past few days, putting the peace process
in grave danger.  
</P>
</TEXT>
