<HEADLINE> Africa Can Become Full Partner in Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday
said Africa can become a full partner in the global community
through building strong economies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said this in a statement addressed to
southern and eastern African transport ministers attending a
meeting in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are discussing the safe skies initiative
unveiled by Clinton during his six-nation African tour in late
March to promote air safety in Africa so as to foster the growth
of aviation services with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The initiative complements the U.S. efforts to conclude "open
skies" agreements with key African countries.
</P>
<P>
"By building strong economies," Clinton said, "We can ensure
that Africa can become a full partner in the global community of
the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
He said in the statement that "by upgrading your airports and
navigation systems, you will improve aviation safety and security
systems."
</P>
<P>
"In turn, this will expand regional and international air
service and promote economic growth and development," the U.S.
president said.
</P>
<P>
The safe skies initiative meeting is being attended by U.S.
Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
Also present are transport ministers from Angola, Ethiopia,
Kenya, Malawi, Namibia, Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
A similar meeting will be held in Dakar, Senegal, for central
and west African transport ministers on July 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
