<HEADLINE> Mandela to Attend S. American Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will attend a South Common Market (MERCOSUR)
summit and visit Argentina and Brazil from July 19 to 25, South
African Foreign Ministry said in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Mandela would address the heads of state of
Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay, Uruguay, Bolivia and Chile, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that a foreign head of state has been
invited to address the MERCOSUR summit," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will also hold separate discussions with leaders of
Chile, Paraguay, Uruguay and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
"The MERCOSUR summit meeting will provide an excellent
opportunity for the president to discuss regional issues
affecting southern Africa and MERCOSUR, especially in the context
of growing globalization and the emergence of new regional
trading blocs," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is South Africa's biggest trading partner in Latin
America, with bilateral trade reaching more than 2.75 billion
Rand (550 million U.S. Dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Trade between South Africa and Argentina stood at 1.6 billion
Rand (320 million U.S. Dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Brazil and Argentina are also the biggest sources of tourism
to South Africa from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is in the process of negotiating a number of
bilateral agreements with Latin American countries, including
Brazil and Argentina, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Once completed, the agreements would enable the enhancement of
relations in various fields between South Africa and the region.
</P>
<P>
MERCOSUR groups Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, with
Chile and Bolivia being its associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
