<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Court Upholds Abortion Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Pretoria High
Court Friday dismissed an application by three Christian groups
to declare the abortion law unconstitutional, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The Christian groups based their case on the argument that the
life of a human being started at conception, that abortion
terminated the life of a human being and that Section 11 of the
South African Constitution applied to an unborn child from the
moment of the child's conception.
</P>
<P>
The defendants including Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma,
however, argued that the fetus was not a bearer of rights in
terms of the constitution, that Section 11 of the constitution
did not preclude the termination of pregnancy in the
circumstances and manner contemplated by the act and that the
right of women to choose to have their pregnancy terminated was
protected under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Judge S.W. Mccreath considered that the fetus is not a legal
persona and that there was no expressed provision in the
constitution affording the fetus legal personality or protection.
</P>
<P>
The ruling immediately sparked mixed reaction in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zuma welcomed the ruling, saying it was a victory for South
African women.
</P>
<P>
"The court ruling will remove uncertainties around the
legality of termination of pregnancy, and help assert women's
right to choose and take decisions affecting their lives," Zuma's
office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The government's Gender Equality Commission echoed Zuma's
words that the ruling was a victory for South African women.
</P>
<P>
"This is a particularly courageous judgment which affirms the
constitutional rights of women," head of the commission legal
department Lisle Gerntholtz said.
</P>
<P>
However, Africa Christian Action said that the ruling was a
travesty of justice. If the right of the members of society is
not upheld, then the Bill of Rights is a worthless piece of
paper." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
