<HEADLINE> Mozambique's GDP up 14 Pc in 1997: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Planning
and Finance Tomaz Salomao announced here Friday that the gross
domestic product (GDP) of the country in 1997 grew by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not give the specific sum of the GDP, but it
is estimated at two billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Salomao promised that the
economy of Mozambique this year will "maintain the momentum of
significant recovery and growth."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the momentum of growth in the first
quarter this year was strong compared to the same period last
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister predicted that the GDP will increase by 10
percent in 1998. The target of the GDP growth for 1998 set by
the Mozambican government is 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the construction sector, the
industrial sector, especially the processing industry, and
transportation sector are among the sectors with rapid growth.
The growth rates in construction and transportation are 16
percent and 22.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Salomao noted that the inflation rate was 6.4 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the reform is slow while the heavy
external debt is seriously hindering the recovery and growth of
the economy in the southern African country. And bureaucratism
can be seen clearly in some departments of the government.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government declared in April that the GDP of
the country grew by eight percent last year. Referring to this,
the planning and finance minister said that according to the
latest statistics, the GDP growth rate in 1997 should be 14
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
