<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Marks World Population Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Activities undertaken to
implement Ethiopia's national population policy in the past five
years have made encouraging achievements, the National Population
Office of Ethiopia said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to mark the World Population Day which
falls on July 11, 1998, Head of the National Population Office,
Nigussie Teferra said major undertakings over the implementation
of the policy in the past few years focused on areas of capacity
building and the creation of integrated working mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the unbalanced population growth in the
sub-Saharan Africa, including Ethiopia, has now become a pressing
issue.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's office has endorsed a study on the
structural framework undertaken by the National Population Office
with a view to alleviating existing manpower shortage, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Teferra, the United Nations Population Fund has
alloted about 28 million U.S.Dollars for the implementation of
the national population policy in the coming four years, and 80
percent of the fund will go into the implementation of the policy
in regions, mainly to the reproductive health care with a view to
minimising the death toll of mothers and children.
</P>
<P>
This year's World Population Day will be observed under the
theme of ''the day of the six billion people'' as it is envisaged
that the world population which now stood at 5.9 billion will
grow to 6 billion next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
