<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dar es Salaam Int'l Trade Fair Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Deputy Minister
of Industry and Commerce, Shamim Khan, said Friday that the 22nd
Dar es Salaam International Trade Fair has been a success.
</P>
<P>
Khan, who closed the fair in the capital city's Saba Saba
grounds in the evening, said the eight-day fair has been
"hectic."
</P>
<P>
She said 320,000 people have visited the fair grounds. And
business visitors are estimated at around 5,000. An entrance
ticket is sold at 700 Shillings (about 1.04 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign countries represented at the fair increased to 23
countries from 17 countries last year, while the total number of
Tanzanian participants reached 600, compared to 589 last year,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Export orders during the fair worth 1.41 million U.S. Dollars
are recorded, whereas import orders worth 3.2 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, sales on the spot have surpassed 1.98 billion
Shillings (about 2.96 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister expressed satisfaction over the success of
the fair, saying "The number of trade inquiries received during
this fair attests to our conviction that the Dar es Salaam
International Fair can be an effective tool for promoting exports
and really serve as a bridge to global trade."
</P>
<P>
Khan said the government will continue to support the
organization in future fairs to make them more successful.
</P>
<P>
She urged members of the business community especially the
private sector to come forward in larger numbers and to play a
more prominent role in the organization and management of
regional trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister's views were shared by K.S. Mwasha, the
Director of Research and Planning of the Board of External Trade
(BET), who said the trade fair is a "very big success."
</P>
<P>
"The exhibitors are happy," he said, adding that some have
expressed willingness to attend next year's fair.
</P>
<P>
The official with the BET, the major organizer, revealed that
an international consumer goods fair will be held in Dar es
Salaam in December this year.
</P>
<P>
The official also highlighted the role of privatization in the
country's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the setting up of more private firms means
more investment and greater job opportunities, which in turn will
increase people's purchasing power and make trade fairs even
booming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
