<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Killed by Ex-Freedom Fighters' Landmine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian resident has
been killed by a landmine abandoned by the former freedom
fighters of the Pan-Africanist Congress of South Africa in a forest
in the Coast Region.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said here Friday that another civilian was
wounded in the incident happened on June 13 in Pongwe Msungula
forest in Bagamoyo District.
</P>
<P>
The area, which was used by the freedom fighters as a camp
during their struggle against the then apartheid regime, has been
restricted and police, in collaboration with the Tanzania
People's Defense Forces (TPDF), have already discovered 73
landmines within two days.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Semiono, whose leg was injured in the blast, was
quoted as saying that he tried to warn his brother Hamisi Said
against playing with an unknown object, but failed.
</P>
<P>
"He opened the lid of the oval object, and there came a sound
which indicated that something dangerous was about to happen,"
Semiono said. "I started running away from him and heard a huge
explosion."
</P>
<P>
Said, 23, was blown up and part of Semiono's right leg was
ripped off by an object.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Foreign Affairs and International
Cooperation, Jakaya Kikwete, has toured the Pongwe Msungula
forest and warned the residents not to visit the area until it
was made safe.
</P>
<P>
Local police told the minister that 15 hectares of land have
been cleared of the landmines, but it was difficult to continue
the search for others because of long grass.  
</P>
</TEXT>
