WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday welcomed a British proposal for indirect talks between
Catholics and Protestants in Northern Ireland to try to end a
dispute over a banned Protestant march through a Catholic area.
</P>
<P>
"The president is very concerned about the violence that has
occurred there," White House spokesman Mike McCurry told a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The president welcomes and applauds the action today by the
government of the United Kingdom to initiate indirect contact
talks between the Orange Order and the residents of Garvaghy
Road," he said.
</P>
<P>
A six-day impasse over the planned parade in the town of
Portadown has been marked by rioting and attacks on police across
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair proposed
that members of the Protestant Orange Order and Roman Catholic
residents from where the march has been banned nominate four
representatives each to discuss their differences on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that kind of dialogue, if it happens tomorrow,
diminishes the violence and encourages people to see that through
talking they can resolve some of the differences that they do
have," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"That would be an expression of faith in the peace process that
the citizens of Northern Ireland have blessed at the ballot box
and made clear that they want to see as the useful tool for the
decisions that need to be made about their own future," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also added that the U.S. will be monitoring those
developments on Saturday as the parties gather to talk. 
</P>
