<HEADLINE> Texas Education Board to Divest Disney Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Texas Board of Education on
Friday voted to dump its 43 million U.S. dollars in Walt Disney
Co. stock in protest against sex, violence and drugs in movies
produced by the company's Miramax subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a 8-4 vote by the board members
after the American Family Association of Texas, which is involved
in a Disney boycott, sent members a videotape of Miramax film
excerpts that included scenes of murder, drug use, according to
an Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
Texas became the first state in the country to rid itself of
Disney stock in protest against the content of its films.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Southern Baptist Convention last year voted to
boycott Disney in protesting against the company's practice of
extending health insurance to same-sex partners of employees and
of having "Gay Days" at its amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
Board Chairman Jack Christie, a Houston Republican, had said he
hoped a vote to divest "sends a message to Miramax... that the
public in general has had enough of exposing children to the
violence and explicitness in these movies."
</P>
<P>
But Claudia Peters, Disney director of corporate
communications, said that film subsidiaries of Disney that produce
movies for mature audiences are set up under other names and
adhere to the rating system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
