<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Meets with U.S. Supreme Court Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Saturday outlined his vision of justice in Europe to a delegation
of U.S. Supreme Court judges.
</P>
<P>
The Elysee presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said the
meeting was ``very friendly, relaxed and trusting'' and was
focused on the issues of European construction and
European-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Chirac told his guests that European countries were committed
to developing and defending what he called the ``social model
proper for Europe'', according to which the government is
responsible for the social cohesion.
</P>
<P>
He said that Europe would become ``a considerable economic,
cultural and political pole'' in the world after the European
Union was enlarged to central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
An enlarged European Union would have 500 million people, a
single market and a single currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said that France paid great importance to relations
between Europe and the United States, which were important for
constructing a multipolar world in the 21st century in "harmony,
balance and consensus''.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Supreme Court delegation comprised four judges: Sandra
Day O'Connor, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Anthony Kennedy and Stephen
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of their visit to France and other European
countries was to compare the judicial systems of the U.S. and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
They will meet with Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and Minister
of Justice Elisabeth Guigou on Monday, and will visit the French
Council of State, the Court de Cassation and the Constitutional
Council, the combination of the three being roughly the equivalent
of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
They will also attend the July 14 French National Day parade on
Champs-Elysee and join the traditional garden party at the Elysee
presidential palace afterwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
