<HEADLINE> Thai Education Ministry Plagued by Corruption Scandals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Corruption scandals have plagued
Thailand's Education Ministry where a number of officials are
facing corruption complaints, according to the Counter Corruption
Commission (CCC).
</P>
<P>
A total of 172 complaints were lodged against education
officials on grounds of corruption and irregularities in 1997, the
commission said in its annual report available Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is among the top three ministries plagued by
corruption scandals, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The other two ministries are the Interior with 361 complaints,
and the Agriculture with 145 complaints.
</P>
<P>
The commission's graft and corruption claims apparently added
weight to the Office of Auditor-General which reported
irregularities involving budget spending at the Education
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Chumpol Silpa-archa revealed earlier that
several education offices did not have receipts for spending
programs, some issued checks to unidentified creditors and those
who signed procurement projects were not authorized persons.
</P>
<P>
Some agencies failed to submit copies of contracts worth more
than one million baht (25,000 U.S. dollars) to the state auditor
and others also failed to collect delay fines, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
But he said he would leave inquiries to the CCC while asking
for detailed information from agencies concerned to keep suspected
officials in check.
</P>
<P>
He said he has assigned the directors-general to closely
monitor spending of agencies under their supervision and make sure
they observe ministerial regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
