<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Improving Quality of Amusement Park Rides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's State Bureau of Quality
and Technology Supervision reported today that some 85 percent of
Chinese amusement park rides meet quality standards.
</P>
<P>
This is much better than in 1996, when it found that only
about 42 percent of the rides qualified.
</P>
<P>
Out of 20 ferris wheels manufactured in the cities of Beijing
and Shanghai, and in Shandong, Liaoning, Hebei, Shaanxi, Sichuan,
Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, 17 were up to standards.
</P>
<P>
There were 19 companies involved. Four of them did not have the
proper permit and only 50 percent of their products passed.
</P>
<P>
Amusement park rides involve questions of safety and are
strictly controlled by the state, but some companies still produce
low-quality rides without any production permit.
</P>
<P>
Quite a few accidents have happened in amusement parks in
recent years because of rides, resulting in serious injuries
and deaths. This has caused a great deal of concern in the
government, which has decided to tighten controls.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau's study did show however that quality awareness has
greatly improved and that the production permit system has
provided quality guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau has told quality supervision departments across the
country to improve inspections of amusement park rides, and to
stop the production of inferior products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Blames S. Africa for Defying Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Romao Mutisse, Magistrate of southern Mozambique's Moamba
County, said Friday that South Africa might have not permitted
water to flow down two cubic meters per second as mutually agreed
upon to the lower reaches of the Incomati River, drying up the
river bed in the county.
</P>
<P>
Mutisse said the South Africans might be preventing water of
the river from flowing down to Mozambican land as they did in
1993/1994, to the neglect of the water sharing agreement between
the two countries, the Noticias reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The magistrate complained that his people have begun to dig for
underground water, but with the rainy season is yet to come by
in November, the effort is far from enough in the county which
began to find even drinking water in short supplies in June, not
to mention the irrigation of crops.
</P>
<P>
Incomati River which originates from South Africa, flows past
Mozambique's Moamba County and drains into the sea near Maputo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
