<HEADLINE> Anti-Drug Campaign in Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Police in southwestern China's
Yunnan Province plan to recruit more people for the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Public Security Bureau established a Narcotics
Bureau and Narcotics Corps today, and they will open offices at
the prefecture and county level, according to Sun Dahong, the
Bureau's director.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2,000 police involved in the drug fight in
Yunnan, which is a major drug conduit to other parts of China from
the Golden Triangle.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1980s, police here have dealt with some 50,000
drug cases and seized more than 70 tons of narcotics, accounting
for 80 percent of China's total.
</P>
<P>
The new agencies are expected to foil drug deals and to tighten
controls on the production and use of drugs, Sun says.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qianrong, of the State Anti-Narcotics Committee, says he
hopes the whole country will help develop drug agencies like
Yunnan has.
</P>
<P>
Top Chinese leaders have asked government at all levels to
increase their work in this area by increasing investment and
recruiting new members.
</P>
<P>
China had at least 540,000 drug users registered by the end of
last year, 85 percent of whom were below the age of 35. More than
70 percent of China's counties have reported cases of drug abuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Electricity Co. in Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Electricity Supply
Corporation (ZESCO) has been plunged into a financial crisis
because of a 100 billion Kwacha debt (about 50 million U.S.
Dollars) owed by the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
ZESCO, as a result, has failed to remit more than 40 billion
Kwacha to the Zambian government in value added tax (VAT) and is
depending on bank overdrafts to pay its workers' salaries, Times
of Zambia reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
British Petroleum has also withdrawn its services from ZESCO
after the company accrued a four billion Kwacha (two million
Dollars). And the petroleum company has now resorted to selling
the corporation only on a cash basis.
</P>
<P>
Other companies ZESCO owes money include the Zambia Metal
Fabricators with two billion Kwacha (one million Dollars) and the
Zambia Forestry and Forest Industries Company with 1.8 billion
Kwacha (900,000 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted ZESCO Managing Director Robinson Mwansa who
unveiled his company's financial woes Thursday as saying that
ZESCO got into financial trouble eight months ago when ZCCM
stopped settling its electricity bills through Copperbelt Energy
Corporation, a customer of the electricity corporation.
</P>
<P>
Last month, ZCCM owed the energy corporation more than 50
million Dollars and the debt keeps rising due to the country's
mining conglomerate's delayed privatization of the two key mining
units -- Nchanga and Nkana, which has driven ZCCM further into
the quagmire, making it fail to pay its huge electricity bills.
</P>
<P>
Mwansa painted a very grim picture about the company's
financial plight and the looming crisis if no measures are taken
to ensure its continued viability.
</P>
<P>
Mwansa said the situation has become so bad that ZESCO is now
failing to buy important materials such as transformers, diesel,
insolation tapes poles and meters for its operations.
</P>
<P>
He added that ZESCO owes nearly every bank in Zambia some
money through overdrafts and warned that if these banks decide to
withdraw the overdraft facility, his company will fail to pay
salaries.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial published on the same day, the paper urged the
government to find a quick solution to this "highly contagious
form of economic pneumonia" that threatens the viability of a
number of companies that rely on the mines for survival.
</P>
<P>
It warned that if the present chain-reaction continues, it
will have dire consequences on the whole economy and render
useless many of the positive economic achievements made so far.
</P>
