<HEADLINE> Beijing Expecting Annual Economic Growth Of Nine Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Mayor Jia Qinglin told a
municipal meeting on the economic situation today that the city
expects to have 9 percent economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
The city has produced 83.9 billion yuan (about 10 billion
U.S. dollars) worth of goods in the first half of the year, an
increase of 9 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports and foreign investment have also seen big
increases. Exports were worth 1.37 billion U.S. dollars, an
increase of 22.9 percent, and foreign investment amounted to 1.02
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 30.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city needs to stick to the central government's
macro-economic controls, the mayor pointed out, and said that the
9.1 percent economic growth in the first half means the city can
reach its yearly economic goal.
</P>
<P>
The city will begin 67 key construction projects and a number
of infrastructure projects in the latter half of the year as part
of the country's 50th anniversary celebrations, Jia
said. Tian'anmen Square and Chang'an Avenue will be thoroughly
refurbished.
</P>
<P>
The city is expected to reach its annual export goal of 2.5
billion U.S. dollars, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
