<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Budget Not Election-oriented: Nepali Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Finance Minister Ram
Saran Mahat said here Saturday that the budget he presented to
parliament Friday for the 1998/99 fiscal year which begins in
mid-July is not election-oriented.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is the budget should be based on the
realities of the country," Mahat told a press conference organized
by the Federation of Nepalese Journalists.
</P>
<P>
"I have done according to the realities of the nation," he
said. "Sustainable development and national interest are taken
into consideration in the budget."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, who came to power in
mid-April, has said that he would announce the date later this
year for general elections in April/May next year.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the economic conditions of the
country are not satisfactory, and the development process has not
found the right path in the past 50 years. "This is due to both
internal and external factors," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the financial crisis in Southeast Asia has
indirectly affected Nepal and the country could not move the
economic mobilization in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
"The new budget will bring about economic activities in the
right path," he said, adding that some arrangements have been made
in the new budget to mobilize the revenues effectively and control
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Mahat said that the new budget has laid emphasis on economic
discipline of the country, proper use of the resources for
productive sectors and the limitation of overdraft to be taken
from the Nepal Rastra Bank, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The budget also stresses the implementation of the program of
"Development in Each Village: Employment in Each Family" to solve
the problem of growing unemployment and rural development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the new budget attaches importance as well to
promoting exports, creating investment environment and making
reform in the industries which are not operating well, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that value added tax (VAT) will be fully implemented in
the country from the coming fiscal year. "We have consulted the
business community and the decision was taken on consensus basis,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal formally introduced the VAT in November 1997 despite
strong opposition from the business community.
</P>
<P>
Mahat disclosed that Japan, Britain, India, Germany, the World
Bank, the Asian Development Bank and other donor countries and
agencies involved in the development of Nepal are committed to
their contributions to the new budget.
</P>
<P>
Of the government's 69.693 billion rupees (1.1 billion U.S.
dollars) budget estimate, 7.772 billion rupees (120 million
dollars) will be met by foreign bilateral and multilateral grant
assistance.
</P>
<P>
And the deficit of 22.442 billion rupees (340 million dollars)
will be covered by foreign bilateral and multilateral loans and
internal loans from the banking and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The parliament will discuss and vote on the budget next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
