<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Development Zones Help Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Development zones in China's
Shandong Province have helped overall economic growth in the
province, Wang Chuntao, director of the provincial Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation Commission, told an investment forum here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They have brought a number of technology-intensive and high
export volume projects to the two state-level economic and
technological development zones in Shandong, in Qingdao and
Yantai, and the 58 province-level economic development areas and
bonded zones.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, there was 13.83 billion yuan in infrastructure
investment in development areas. Some, like the Asian, Taiwan,
Singapore, and South Korea industrial parks, are up to
international standards.
</P>
<P>
Wang says that 6.84 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign funds
had been committed to the development zones by the end of last
year, and 3 billion dollars of that was in place. The zones have
3,241 projects.
</P>
<P>
Large international conglomerates like Siemens, Thyssen,
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Daewoo Cement, Hyundai Motors, Chase
Manhattan Bank, and Pittsburg Plate Glass have also invested in
the zones.
</P>
<P>
Waste water treatment facilities of the Qingdao development
area have attracted the interest of American and Japanese business
people. 
</P>
