<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Varsity Pledges Tough Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The council and administration of
the University of Zimbabwe has pledged tougher conditions which
will guarantee normalization of activities at the troubled
institution of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Friday's graduation ceremony officiated by
chancellor of the university and President Robert Mugabe, council
Chairman Gideon Gono said his council was aware that the majority
of innocent students wedoe being inconvenienced by the temporary
closure of the institution, the Daily Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said, appropriate disciplinary action will be taken against
those mentally and physically disposed to violence as the only
way to solve problems.
</P>
<P>
"My council will put in place a new set of rules and
regulations, which will ensure that all stake-holders bear a
certain minimum level of responsibility for the well-being and
behavior of students," Gono said.
</P>
<P>
Five students, including three student leaders, have since
been suspended and are expected to appear before a disciplinary
committee soon to answer allegations of incitement, intimidation
and riotous behavior during the last demonstration which turned
violent.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 4,000 students graduated from the university Friday
under a new format, which saw one ceremony being held instead of
the previous arrangement that stretched the event over two days.
