<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Tobacco's Price Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- While there has been a marked
improvement in the average price of Zimbabwean tobacco, experts
have predicted the price will not go beyond 1.75 U.S. Dollars per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Herald Saturday reported a total of 106 million kgs
have so far been sold at prices ranging from 1.27 U.S. Dollars a
kg to 1.96 Dollars a kg.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have earned three billion Zimbabwean Dollars (106
million Dollars) from more than half of the flue-cured tobacco
crop reduced this season.
</P>
<P>
Flue-cured tobacco is being sold at 1.71 Dollars a kg in
Brazil and Zimbabwe needs to maintain its prices at almost the
same level, in order to retain the market share it has enjoyed
for years, Brazil and Zimbabwe are two O the main tobacco
producers in the world.
</P>
<P>
Market information director of the Zimbabwe Tobacco
Association Pat Davis Friday said although prices had started
firming after weeks of waiting by farmers, they would not reach
last season's levels because of problems in the United States and
the Far East.
</P>
<P>
Last season the crop fetched an average price of 2.4 Dollars a
kg, which would be difficult to beat in view of the problems on
the world market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
