<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG May Become African Standing Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping
ECOMOG may soon transform into an African standing force for the
resolution of conflicts in the continent, the Daily Times
reported Saturday, quoting ECOMOG chief, Maj.-Gen. Timothy
Shelpidi.
</P>
<P>
When the proposed force comes on stream, it will operate like
those of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the United
Nations, Shelpidi told a recent sub-regional forum on conflict
management and resolution in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, a military arm of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), is known for its successful
peace-keeping operations in Liberia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the biggest contributor of troops, funding and
logistics to ECOMOG, has proposed to turn it into a continental
standing force.
</P>
<P>
"The composition of such a standing force will comprise
military and paramilitary troops from member states contributing
to such organizations," the Nigerian general stated.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi, however, described differences in language, training
of armed forces, equipment and orientation as some of the
problems that ought to be settled to ensure smooth operation of
the proposed force.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, led to command and kitting problems and delay
in troop deployment.
</P>
<P>
The force commander called for central funding for the peace
keeping force to avoid the current financial problems of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
"The case of Liberia, for instance, where some of the
contributing countries to the ECOMOG had to depend on other
countries within and outside the sub-region for sponsorship for
them to participate in the peace keeping activities is not the
best," Shelpidi said.
</P>
<P>
Financial problems also handicapped some countries willingness
to contribute troops to ECOMOG for operations in Sierra Leone, he
pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Industry Minister Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The High Court of Tanzania
has unseated Sengerema Member of Parliament William Shija, who is
also the Minister of Industry and Commerce, after declaring his
1995 general election results in the constituency null and void.
</P>
<P>
Shija has therefore, automatically lost his ministerial post,
becoming a second minister that was forced to step down in two
months in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Reading a nine-hour judgement Friday, Judge Anthony Mrema
declared the elections void because election regulations were
violated, media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Judge Mrema said Shija, who was then the Mwanza Regional
Commissioner, did not resign his post before he contested in the
Sengerema constituency, a violation of the Election Act.
</P>
<P>
The judge also said that many polling stations were not opened
in time, making 17,489 registered voters fail to vote.
</P>
<P>
In the elections, Shija scooped 19,917 votes against 13,080
votes won by Fortunatus Masha of the opposition United Democratic
Party (UDP).
</P>
<P>
Shija was absent from the court when the judgement was read.
He was represented by his counsel.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Shija follows that of Sebastian Kinyondo, who was
unseated by the High Court as MP for Bukoba rural constituency in
late May. The judgement made Kinyondo lose his position as the
Minister of Labor and Youth Development.
</P>
<P>
Kinyondo was charged with corruption and using abusive
language against others in his 1995 election campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Women Have High Birth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Angolan women enjoy the highest
birth rate among central African countries, with every woman
giving birth to an average of 7.2 children.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Population Fund office in Angola revealed
this to the press here Friday at the eve of the tenth World
Population Day.
</P>
<P>
According to the Population Fund, the main reason for the high
birth rate is early marriage and sex life, low education level on
the part of women as well as traditional family mode of
multitude.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Population Fund show that the birth rate
for an average Zambian woman is 6.4, for Tanzanian woman is 5.5,
whereas in the Democratic Republic of Congo the rate is 6.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the U.N. Population Fund has allocated a total of
15 million U.S. Dollars for Angola during the year 1997 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's World Population Day is "to
establish a healthy and protected society." Starting from
Saturday to next Friday, Angola will launch a series of
activities to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Currently Angola's population stands at nearly 12 million, one
third of which are under 30 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Due to long years of civil war, the population in the southern
African country is concentrated mainly in cities and their
environs, with very few people dwelling in the countryside. About
one fourth of the total population are residing in the area near
the capital Luanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0097 </DOCNO>
