<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Live Courtroom Hearing On Television </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of millions of Chinese
television viewers were able to watch a courtroom hearing in
Beijing live this morning when China's Central Television (CCTV)
broadcast one for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Legal scholars hailed the move an important way to promote
legal reforms and public involvement in law-enforcement, and a new
development toward a democratic legal system.
</P>
<P>
It is also a breakthrough in media reporting, said Wang Yi, a
researcher at the Chinese Academy of Sciences' National Conditions
Analysis and Research Group. Wang said CCTV carried three major
events in about two weeks live: President Jiang Zemin's press
conference with President Clinton, Clinton's speech at Beijing
University, and this court case.
</P>
<P>
"These show the world that China's decision makers are more
self-confident, open-minded, and willing to trust people to make
their own judgement," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The trial was in Beijing's No. 1 Intermediate People's Court,
presided over by a panel of judges, headed by Judge Sun Jian. It
involved a suit brought by 10 Chinese film studios against 3
companies which were accused of copyright violations in the case
of 27 feature films.
</P>
<P>
The judges delivered their first verdict after four hours of
debate and ordered the 3 defendants to pay 480,000 yuan in
compensation for copyright violations, and told them not to repeat
the offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Live Courtroom Hearing on Television (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CCTV also invited two legal scholars on hand to explain to the
audience the legal issues involved and to answer questions over
the phone.
</P>
<P>
The decision to allow a live broadcast came when Xiao Yang, the
newly-elected president of the Supreme People's Court, said
recently that the media could cover some trials, but that the media
would be held responsible for getting the facts right. So, the
live broadcast drew a lot of of attention.
</P>
<P>
Law professors and legal scholars said, in telephone
interviews, that the parties involved were able to express their
views well, and that the judges' decision was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
But, according to Gao Mingxuan, vice-president of the China Law
Society and prominent professor of law, what was most significant
was not the case itself, but the significant breakthrough in the
open trials. Although it is provided for in the Chinese
constitution, it has not really been done, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Usually, people who want to attend a hearing need to get a pass
outside the courthouse with their ID card.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiayang, deputy director of People's University's
Communications Research Institute, calls the live broadcast
"inevitable".
</P>
</TEXT>
