<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Live Courtroom Hearing on Television (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Bo, one of the defense lawyers, acknowledged that having to
face people all across the country during in the trial, as well as
the judges and lawyers, demanded high standards, and said he
thinks that open trials will promote equity and justice.
</P>
<P>
The foreign media also paid close attention to the event and
many foreign journalists were present at the court and talked to
people on the street. Beijing residents also showed great interest
in it.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma Aidi, president of Beijing's No.1 People's
Court, Chinese courts have long tried to reform trial methods to
safeguard justice and build a democratic legal system.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 local television channels have shown trials in the past
or excerpts of trials in cooperating with local courts. Some
were even in live telecasts.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Supreme People's Court promises that the
SPC will repeat today's practice across the country by examining
the experience and will develop rules for live broadcasts of
future court trials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
