<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Raises Panel on New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military government
has set up a special committee to study various views expressed
during a nationwide consultation on the country's transition to
civil rule program and make its recommendations to the
government.
</P>
<P>
The Flag Officer of the Eastern Naval Command, Rear Admiral
Victor Ombu, made this known at the end of a meeting of the
highest ruling body, the Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), in
Abuja, the Daily Times said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ombu did not name the members of the committee, but the
newspaper said it comprises mainly PRC members.
</P>
<P>
The committee will make recommendations on the fate of the
country's five political parties, the various transition agencies
and previous elections held under the transition program three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
It will submit a report next week to enable the PRC make its
final decision on the way forward, the report said, adding the
decision will be known in a broadcast by new leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
According to late leader Sani Abacha's transition program, the
military will return Nigeria to a civilian government on October
1, 1998 after a presidential election on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was, until his sudden death on June 8, the consensus
presidential candidate of the five parties.
</P>
<P>
Following his death, there have been suggestions that the
parties registered by him should be dissolved, the transition
agencies restructured and all previous elections canceled.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has been calling for the cancellation of the
whole transition program. They want the military to hand over to
Moshood Abiola, the believed winner of the annulled June 12, 1993
presidential election, who had been in jail for four years.
</P>
<P>
But that was made impossible by the sudden death of Abiola on
July 7, just as he was discussing his release with Abubakar and a
high-powered U.S. delegation headed by Under Secretary of State,
Thomas Pickering.
</P>
<P>
The military has been strong pressured from both home and
abroad to implement a rapid transition to civil rule, but there
are also suggestions that the transition should not be such a
rush so as to damage the power basis of the coming civilian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
