<HEADLINE> Young People Go on Expedition to Remote Chinese Countryside (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of young people between
the ages of 17 and 25 from 11 different countries began a
ten-week expedition on China's Great Wall today.
</P>
<P>
The group has 31 college students from China and 90 from
Britain, Argentina, Chile, Italy, Japan, Jordan, Malaysia, Oman,
Singapore and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The "Inchcape Initiative" gives the young adventurers a chance
to go to remote mountainous areas and villages in Shandong and
Jiangsu Provinces, where they will help local farmers build three
primary schools and four small irrigation dams.
</P>
<P>
They will also camp out at two nature reserves in Jiangsu for
David's deer and red-crowned cranes, which are endangered species,
where they will build an observation tower and animal compounds.
</P>
<P>
The expedition was started by Britain's Raleigh International,
a charitable organization that helps young people understand
themselves better for personal development.
</P>
<P>
Natascha Uberbacher, a Raleigh spokeswoman, says that her
organization has frequently recruited young people worldwide to go
to developing countries to do various challenging community and
environmental projects to help them get more experience and
understand their own potential.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Chinese government has encouraged the
younger generation to get some experience and improve themselves
through social work, to build themselves up physically and
mentally by working under harsh conditions, and to learn the
virtues of selflessness and dedication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young People Go on Expedition to Remote Chinese Countryside (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Raleigh has organized 125 expeditions in 35 countries for
15,000 young people since 1984, Uberbacher says, but this is the
first one in China, where they are working with the China Youth
Development Foundation (CYDF). Education and environmental
protection are two very important issues in China today, she says.
</P>
<P>
CYDF began the "Hope Project" in 1989 and, over the past eight
years, it has helped over 1.5 million school drop-outs in
poverty-stricken areas return to school. It has also provided
funding for at least 3,600 primary schools in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Gan Dongyu, deputy director of CYDF's International Department,
says that the Raleigh International China Expedition is the first
of its kind in China. The participants will do some concrete and
useful things for small communities, instead of visiting major
cities and just sitting and chatting with each other, he points
out, and this will help them improve practical skills and will
give the foreign youth a good opportunity to understand China.
</P>
<P>
Everyone will prove to be valuable, one young British member of
the team says, and they will be able and glad to do more hard
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
