<HEADLINE> 393 Persons Removed From Cambodian Electoral Register </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A total of 393 persons,
including 157 dead and 23 under-age, have been removed from the
electoral register of Cambodia, in the run-up to the general
election on July 26.
</P>
<P>
The move came after examination of reports received from the
Province Election Committee (PEC) and Commune Election Committee
(CEC) in 21 provinces, Cambodia's National Election Committee
(NEC) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Besides the dead and the under-age, 127 were registered more
than once, 78 were not Cambodian citizens, three presented wrong
documents, and five moved house, said HE Samraing Kamsan, advisor
to the NEC chairman.
</P>
<P>
"This is only the first step. The NEC is considering the
removal of around 1,000 further persons from the electoral
register, but no decision has yet been made," he said.
</P>
<P>
Transportation of the 12,500 ballot boxes and election
materials to the 11,699 polling stations was still underway, the
advisor said, adding all would be in place for the PECs by July
20, and by July 24 for the CECs.
</P>
<P>
But the office said the NEC still faced difficulties in
transportation.
</P>
<P>
The NEC had to use trucks, boats, planes, horse-carts, ox-carts
and even elephants to carry the election equipment, especially to
remote provinces, such as Mondolkiri and Rattanakiri, he said.
</P>
<P>
NEC officials also invited journalists to test the indelible
ink offered by India which will identify those who have already
voted on polling day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
