<HEADLINE> Fans' Behavior outside "Acceptable": Johansson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The behavior of soccer fans outside the
World Cup stadiums was "acceptable" despite the violences in Marseille
and Lens, FIFA's World Cup Organizing Committee Chairman Lennart
Johansson said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"All of you are aware of the incidents in Marseille and Lens,"
Lennart told a news conference. "But I must say that overall even so
the crowd behavior outside the stadium before and after the matches
are acceptable."
</P>
<P>
French gendarme Daniel Nivel was beaten into a coma by German
hooligans in Lens on June 21, when Germany and Yugoslavia met in a
group game.
</P>
<P>
In Marseille, England and Tunisian fans had clashed on a beach,
resulting arrests and deportation of England fans.
</P>
<P>
Johansson said the tournament was generally a success and his job
as the chairman of the FIFA organizing committee was very easy.
</P>
<P>
"As a chairman I have an easy job. Almost everything went
perfectly," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Johansson said the images of shirt-pulling on the pitch left
him a bad impression.
</P>
<P>
As to the refereeing, Johansson said FIFA was considering using
more modern technology.
</P>
<P>
"We're thinking about the possiblities of using modern technologies
in some specific situations," he said.
</P>
<P>
FIFA President Sepp Blatter has criticized on Friday the failure of
the Disciplinary Committee to use video footage to sanction players'
serious fouls that referees failed to spot on the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
