<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian President Concerned at Growing Cancer Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan expressed concern at the growing incidence of cancer in
his country, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Out of an estimated 9 million cancer patients in the world, 50
percent are in India," PTI quoted Narayanan as saying in Mumbai
where he inaugurated the silver jubilee celebrations of a hospital
named Jaslok and a research center.
</P>
<P>
Despite specialized knowledge and expertise gained by Indian
medical fraternity over the years, Narayanan said, the number of
cancer patients would rise to 6.5 million in the country by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Narayanan, who arrived in the country's financial city this
morning for his first visit since he took over as president just
one year ago, called on the medical fraternity to undertake
extensive research on people's lifestyle and shift their attention
from curative to preventive aspects of illness.
</P>
<P>
Preventive aspect has become even more important than curative
aspect, he said, adding that state-of-the-art equipment is
impressive but there is need to focus on the human factor in
medicine as most diseases emanate from living conditions and diet.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
