<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Golkar Elects New Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Minister/Secretary of
State Akbar Tanjung was elected as new general chairman of the
country's ruling Golkar (Functional Group) here Saturday
afternoon, replacing outgoing Golkar chairman Harmoko.
</P>
<P>
The election was conducted at the end of a three-day
extraordinary congress of the party. As many as 17 out of 27
Golkar provincial chapters, all of which hold voting rights,
supported Akbar's nomination and 10 others supported former
Defense Minister Edi Sudradjat.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old Akbar began his political career in Golkar and
previously served as state minister of youth affairs and sports
and state minister for housing. He was described by the local
press as a favorite choice of President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after his election, Akbar said his main
task is to consolidate the organization, with the aim to achieve
success in the future.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Akbar promised to accommodate Golkar cadres who are
forward-looking and highly dedicated, including supporters of
rival Edi Sudradjat, once he is elected the organization's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Election of Golkar's new chairman is the most important item on
the agenda of the congress, which was opened by Habibie on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Habibie said Golkar leader should be chosen by
"those at the bottom" of the organization and not by "those at the
top."
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election was the first time that Golkar's chairman
was determined through voting rather than consensus.
</P>
<P>
Golkar was established in 1964 as an amalgamation of seven
organizations which include the armed forces, labor organizations
and cooperative movements. It has been a dominant political
organization in nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
The organization, which won all the seven general elections in
the past, grabbed 325 of the 425 seats up for election in the
House of Representatives in the May general elections last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Golkar has split into several groups since former
President Soeharto stepped down on May 21 this year. Soeharto was
the chairman of the organization's Board of Patrons, which has an
enormous power including the authority to freeze Golkar's
executive board.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said earlier that another item on the agenda
of the Golkar extraordinary congress was discussion on the removal
of the Board of Patrons.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that all 27 delegations from the regional
chapters said they would be happy if Golkar is turned into a
political party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
