<HEADLINE> 33-day World Cup to Have 10-minute Closing Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The 33-day long World Cup finals will
come to an end with a 10-minute closing ceremony after the final
match between France and Brazil at Stade de France in Saint-Denis on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony will be directed by Yves Pepin, who also
directed the opening ceremony on June 10 at Stade de France stadium.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony will pay a last tribute to the 32 teams
participated in the World Cup finals and at the same time, usher in
2002 World Cup which will be co-hosted by Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
According to the organisers, the closing ceremony will feature
in four different scenes. It will begin with the "Parade des
Tapageurs", a colorful fanfare of 50 musicials and acrobats. The
parade will be followed by "La course des Joyeux" in which 63 torch
carriers parading down the pitch in a spectacle of fire and light.
</P>
<P>
The third scene, which is titled "A Salute to 2002", will
showcase South Korean and Japanese percussionists who will link
France'98 to the next World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
In the final scene, the roof of the Stade de France will begin
to move and rockets will light up and fly away as the stadium "takes
off".
</P>
<P>
Before the final match, there will also be a Yves Saint Laurent
fashion show and a concert and other festivities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
