<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Mount Merapi Erupts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Mount Merapi, Indonesia's most
active volcano, erupted three times Saturday morning followed by
big bursts of hot clouds, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The eruption emitted hot lava that flowed seven kilometers down
toward the western slope of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
No casualties have been reported, but authorities have warned
the public in areas around the volcano to get ready for
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted officials of the Directorate of Volcanology
as saying they cannot predict the further development of the
eruption, because the mountain was still covered by thick smokes
at noon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mount Merapi, 2,968 meters high, is situated in Central Java,
the most densely populated region of Java Island. It is the most
active volcano in the country and one of most active volcanoes in
the world.
</P>
<P>
The volcano's last eruption was in January 1997, when more than
8,000 nearby villagers had to be evacuated after the volcano
spewed hot gas, ash and lava over its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Merapi's most destructive eruption this century was in 1930,
when 1,300 people were killed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
