<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Hopeful of Reducing Population Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif expressed his hope Saturday that his country will achieve
its target of bringing down the population growth rate to 2.1
percent from 2.6 in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a day-long National Population Convention, held to
observe the World Population Day, he said the population growth
rate of Pakistan has already come down from 2.7 to 2.6 percent at
present.
</P>
<P>
He noted that an increase in population has direct relations
with illiteracy, which could be overcome by giving equal education
opportunities to both rural and urban societies.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, is well aware of Islamic values and
will not ignore these rights while promoting population planning.
</P>
<P>
Population planning is meant to provide a better standard of
life to people and ensure better utilization of their mental
faculties, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called upon religious scholars to create awareness among the
general public about the population welfare program.
</P>
<P>
Referring to increasing population in urban areas, Sharif said
one of the main reasons for it is migration of people from rural
areas to cities.
</P>
<P>
This has over-burdened the existing civic facilities in the
cities while creating many social problems, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This trend has to be checked by providing employment
opportunities, educational and health facilities in rural areas,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said the majority of Pakistanis live in
rural areas and they need to have the basic necessities of life
which include access to clean drinking water, education, health
and recreation.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we strike a balance between the population and our
resources, the people cannot have prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"It is the duty of the government to provide basic amenities to
every child including the right of education but we must have a
check on our population," Sharif added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for providing educational facilities in
rural areas and said they must not be conformed to the cities
only.
</P>
<P>
"With a majority of the population living in small towns and
rural areas, the women there must have a right to education for an
educated future generation.
</P>
<P>
"The child has his early education and guidance from mother and
if she is illiterate one cannot expect to have a society which
will be organized and the one which will prosper," he said.
</P>
<P>
Recreational facilities for a healthy society are also
necessary, Sharif pointed out. He called upon educational
institutions to make sports an essential part of their education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
