<HEADLINE> Mozambique Blames S. Africa for Defying Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Romao Mutisse, Magistrate of southern Mozambique's Moamba
County, said Friday that South Africa might have not permitted
water to flow down two cubic meters per second as mutually agreed
upon to the lower reaches of the Incomati River, drying up the
river bed in the county.
</P>
<P>
Mutisse said the South Africans might be preventing water of
the river from flowing down to Mozambican land as they did in
1993/1994, to the neglect of the water sharing agreement between
the two countries, the Noticias reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The magistrate complained that his people have begun to dig for
underground water, but with the rainy season is yet to come by
in November, the effort is far from enough in the county which
began to find even drinking water in short supplies in June, not
to mention the irrigation of crops.
</P>
<P>
Incomati River which originates from South Africa, flows past
Mozambique's Moamba County and drains into the sea near Maputo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
