<HEADLINE> Turkey to Boost Economic Cooperation with Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz will fly to Bulgaria Saturday on a one-day visit to boost
economic cooperation with the neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure at the Ankara Esengoba Airport, Yilmaz
said Turkey will secure its contributions to the development of
economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Terming the recent bilateral ties "very positive," Yilmaz noted
that he will inaugurate the Sofia branch office of the Turkish
state-owned Ziraat Bank, and the free trade agreement between the
two countries will be signed during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yilmaz said he will also discuss with Bulgarian
officials regional issues, especially the latest status in the
Kosovo crisis, and the prospect for Turkish businessmen to develop
infrastructure projects in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The tensions in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo have heightened
since February when bloody clashes erupted between Serbian police
and ethnic Albanians who, making up 90 percent of the population
in Kosovo, demand independence from Belgrade. 
</P>
