<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's IPI Down for January-May This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's industrial
production index (IPI) for January-May this year fell by 3 percent
to 146.3 from 150.9 registered during the same period of 1997,
according to the Statistics Department Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decline was only due to a drop in the index for the
manufacturing division to 150.9 from 158.8 a year earlier, the
latest IPI figures released by the department show.
</P>
<P>
The index for the mining division however rose by 0.5 percent
to 123.9 while that for the electricity division increased by 6.3
percent to 169.2, the figures show.
</P>
<P>
The IPI is a measure of the rate of change in the production of
industrial commodities in real terms over time.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the index for the mining division in the first
five months of this year was due to rises in the indices of tin
and crude oil by 9.8 percent to 53.9 and 1 percent to 112.2
respectively. In contrast, the index for natural gas dropped 0.8
percent to 183.2.
</P>
<P>
The increasing index for the electricity division was the
result of a 6.4-percent jump in the generation of electricity to
24,033 million kilowatt-hours from 22,596 million kilowatt-hours
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the manufacturing division, six out of a total of 23 major
groups recorded higher indices during the period under review with
the manufacturing of plastic products witnessing the largest
increase of 21.2 percent to 251.7 points. It was followed by the
professional and scientific, and measuring and controlling
equipment group which rose 6.3 percent to 121.3 and the rubber
products group soaring 5 percent to 147.9.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco manufacturers group registered a 4.6-percent rise
to 119.4 and the electrical machinery, apparatus, appliances and
supplies group gained 2.5 percent to 178.4 while the paper and
paper products group rose 0.2 percent to 131. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
