<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Invests in Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
allocated 50 million Shillings (850,000 U.S. Dollars) to finance
oil exploration in the belief that there could be commercially
viable oil reserves in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The government would continue funding oil exploration with
money collected through the petroleum levy paid by oil companies,
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae was quoted Saturday by the Daily
Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged the National Oil Corporation of Kenya
(NOCK) to move quickly in transforming itself to a commercially
viable entity to face the competition.
</P>
<P>
The government would support plans by NOCK to convert into a
fully fledged oil company operating in all areas of the oil
business, Nyachae said Friday.
</P>
<P>
NOCK Chairman Bethuel Ogot said the NOCK will use the
government allocation to upgrade truck loading facilities in
Mombasa and Nairobi, the two largest commercial hubs in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of loading facilities in these areas has been one of our
major problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996/97 (July/June) financial year, the company's
turnover stood at 567 million Shillings (9.6 million Dollars), a
drop from the 1995/96 turnover of 2.2 billion Shillings (37.3
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decline in turnover was attributed to a 30 percent loss of
market share after the liberalization of the oil industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
