<HEADLINE> Kenya Expected to Lead in World's Tea Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is poised to regain its
leading position in the export of black tea from Sri Lanka
following a bumper crop in the first half of this year, commodity
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains interspersed with generous spells of sunshine led
to high growth levels with production surpassing previous records
in the east African country during the first quarter of this
year, the Kenya Time newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"This year we are headed for a bumper crop. Production figures
reflect a huge rise. They are much, much higher compared to both
last year and 1996," Norman Wilson, managing director of Africa
Tea Brokers, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Africa Tea Brokers said in a statement that \Uoduction rose
57.75 million kilograms or 71.77 percent to 138.22 million
kilograms in the first five months of 1998 from the same period
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Production in the January-May period in 1996 was posted at
116.43 million kilograms. That year Kenya's tea yield touched a
record high of 257 million kilograms, making the country the
world's largest tea exporter with 244-million-kilogram tea
exporting.
</P>
<P>
Tea appears to be the only commodity that gained from the El
Nino rains which ruined Kneya's long neglected infrastructure,
mainly roads, bringing big losses to its tourism industry, and
heavily damaged the coffee crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
