<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Curb Prevalence of Selling Small State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's State Economic and Trade
Commission called for curbing the prevalence of selling small
state-owned enterprises, stressing that different forms or
measures be taken in reforming the enterprises in accordance with
their specific situation.
</P>
<P>
In a notice issued Friday, the commission refutes the idea that
sale of small state-owned enterprises is the sole solution to
their restructuring, and suggests enterprises take varied measures
that suit their asset organization mode.
</P>
<P>
These measures include reorganization, merger, lease, contract
management and shareholding, according to the notice.
</P>
<P>
The notice says that in dealing with restructuring the small
state-owned enterprises, government officials in some localities
overemphasized the role enterprise sales plays in the reform
drive.
</P>
<P>
They simplified the restructuring that is expected to be
complicated and effort-taking to "selling," the notice says,
adding that the practice has exerted negative impact on local
economic development and social stability, and the relocation of
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
People in charge of restructuring such enterprises should be
far-sighted, and must not force employees to become share holders,
the document says.
</P>
<P>
It stresses that the evasion and abandoning of financial
liabilities should be prevented in the restructuring drive.
</P>
<P>
The notice calls for proper asset assessment, and reinforced
inspection on employee relocation scheme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
