<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Meizhou Island Attracts Mazu Pilgrims and Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Meizhou Island in east China's
Fujian Province has developed rapidly since 1992 when it was
approved as a national holiday resort.
</P>
<P>
Its tourism programs feature the Mazu culture. Mazu, known as
"the Goddess of Peace of the Strait," is believed to have been
born on Meizhou Island.
</P>
<P>
The island still preserves the world's first Mazu temple, which
is considered the "ancestor" of other 3,000 Mazu temples
scattering in more than 20 countries and regions, with nearly 200
million followers. There are 16 million Mazu followers in Taiwan,
accounting for 75 percent of the total population of the island
province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than one million Mazu
pilgrims coming over to Meizhou every year, one tenth of which are
from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Meizhou invested more than 500 million yuan in infrastructure
construction since 1992. Projects include Mazu temple architecture
groups, 11 kilometer cross-the-island road, and a tap water plant
with a daily supply capacity of 3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, Meizhou has signed more than 50
investment contracts or agreements worth 1.8 billion yuan or
220,000 U.S. dollars, more than half of which have been put into
use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
