<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 06:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teams Set up to Monitor Pollution in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has decided to set up
six emergency teams to monitor various pollutants around the
clock, in a new effort to prevent environmental deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Al Sarawi, chairman and director general of the
Environment Public Authority (EPA), was quoted by the English
daily Arab Times as saying that one of the teams will work on
monitoring emissions in the country's southern areas.
</P>
<P>
Another team will be formed to monitor maritime pollution,
and conduct field studies and monitor coastal water pollution and
report any oil spills to EPA, Sarawi said.
</P>
<P>
He said another team will be responsible for monitoring
contamination that might be caused by drain water or oil spills,
in addition to detecting offenders.
</P>
<P>
The Arid Area and Coasts Evolution Department of EPA will
preside over another team to conduct a comprehensive survey of the
country's coasts, including the three Kuwaiti islands, in order
to keep track of tide movements and its effects on Kuwaiti coasts
and the coastal environment in general.
</P>
<P>
Sarawi said two other teams, which are supervised respectively
by Life Resources Department and Industrial Environment
Department, will monitor the damage that sea creatures might
suffer and follow up factory emissions and their effect on the
country's environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
