<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hashimoto's Fate Ties with Sunday's Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 11 (Xinhua) -- With the 18th election of Japan's
upper chamber coming on Sunday, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
is expected to face a crucial test of whether voters still have
confidence in his leadership.
</P>
<P>
The results of the election of the House of Councillors, which
is the upper house of Japanese parliament, are not expected to
immediately change the government because the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) still dominates the more powerful lower
house, the House of Representatives, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
But they pointed out in the same breath that any serious
setback for the LDP in the election would dramatically affect
Hashimoto's political fate.
</P>
<P>
One focal point of the race is whether the LDP can recover a
majority in the 252-member chamber by securing at least 69 seats.
</P>
<P>
Failing that, the LDP could still score something of a victory
by grabbing 64 seats, a bare majority of the 126 seats being
contested.
</P>
<P>
In either of the above scenarios, LDP officials said, Hashimoto
could be expected to remain as LDP head and serve out his tenure
as prime minister until September 1999.
</P>
<P>
But, if the LDP fails to hold onto its 61 seats that are up for
grabs in the poll, Hashimoto would probably be forced to step
down, throwing Japan's political landscape into turmoil, analysts
believed.
</P>
<P>
Recent newspaper surveys, however, forecast that the LDP will
unlikely accomplish a comeback by regaining a majority in the
upper house lost nine years ago. The LDP might even fail to retain
its 61 seats being contested due to pollees' dissatisfaction with
the government's economic policy.
</P>
<P>
In the past six months, the economic policies of the Japanese
government and the LDP have been widely and severely criticized
for contributing to Japan's economic recession, considered by the
economists the worst in decades.
</P>
<P>
Public support rates for Hashimoto's cabinet also remain at
record-low levels lately amid lacking of signs of improvement in
the Japanese economy despite a series of stimulating measures
unveiled by the government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties, in their campaignings, also criticized the
Hashimoto cabinet for mismanaging the economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the gloomy economic climate and the LDP's declining
popularity, it is still too early to assert that the LDP is
destined to suffer setbacks in the election.
</P>
<P>
The LDP is still likely to make steady gains by making most of
the disarray of the opposition parties, some political pundits
believe.
</P>
<P>
Voter turnout, another focal point of the election, is also
expected to have a great influence on the election results. A
record-low turnout, even lower than the 44.52 percent turnout in
the previous election in 1995, is possible when considering the
growing public apathy towards politics.
</P>
<P>
A low turnout will benefit the LDP because it has strong
support from voter organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The result of the election is predictable if the voter turnout
stands at less than 45 percent, the LDP will expand its strength,"
an analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Some 99.40 million people -- 48.24 million men and 51.16
million women -- are eligible to vote in the poll, marking a 2.1
percent rise from the 1995 election.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese upper chamber is reshuffled every three years for
half the 252 seats, with its members serving a fixed six-year term.
</P>
<P>
A total of 474 candidates from 14 parties and groups are
contesting in the upper house poll. Some 325 candidates are
expected to run in prefectural constituencies for 76 seats, and
some 160 are standing for 50 proportional representation seats.
</P>
<P>
The LDP is fielding 87 candidates, 30 for the proportional
representation slots, under which voters cast their ballots for a
party rather than for an individual, and 57 for prefectural
constituencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
