<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Bans Avopacin in Animal Feed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Agriculture and
Cooperation Ministry has banned Avopacin as an ingredient in
animal feed in order to ensure that Thai chicken exports to Japan
have no Vancomycin-resistant enterococ (VRE) bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The ban took effect on July 7 and the Japanese government has
been notified, said deputy minister Somchai Sunthorvut, quoted by
Saturday's Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Somchai said the ministry will send a mission to Japan next
week to meet with Japanese Public Health Ministry officials. He
said he would ask Japan to inspect the export quality of chicken
products from Thailand as a further precaution.
</P>
<P>
Japan earlier announced that VRE bacteria had been found in
chicken imports from Thailand and France. VRE is dangerous
bacteria with a resistance to antibiotics. However, the bacteria
can be eliminated at high temperature.
</P>
<P>
In the livestock industry, Avopacin is a substance which
farmers mix in feed meal in order to speed up the maturity of
animals. However, local farms stopped using this ingredient five
years ago due to the high price and because it was rejected by
chicken exporters.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has imported nine tons of Avopacin annually over the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
To ensure Thailand's export quality, the ministry has set up a
committee to closely monitor the cause of the problems.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand's chicken exports will not be damaged by attacks in
the Japanese media thanks to our high quality processing lines,"
Somchai said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no change in the orders placed by Japanese
importers and no shipments have been returned," said Anan
Sirimongkolkasem, president of the Thai Broiler Processing
Exporters' Association.
</P>
<P>
Thai chicken exports to Japan totaled 102,756 tons during the
first five months of 1998. The association expects exports to
reach 240,007 tons by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980711.0154 </DOCNO>
