<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Agrees to Cover Deficit for ASIAD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
agreed to cover a 2.5 billion rupiah (164,000 U.S. dollars)
deficit in the National Sports Council's budget for the country's
participation in the Asian Games in Bangkok in December, local
press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by State Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports
Agung Laksono here Friday.
</P>
<P>
After the council said it was finding it difficult to meet its
estimated budget of 5.2 billion rupiah for the national team's
preparations and costs during the competition, the minister said,
the National Development Planning Board had decided to provide the
additional funds.
</P>
<P>
Agung said there would be no more financial aid for the
council.
</P>
<P>
"This is the last. We cannot give more due to the current
economic situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government had promised to allot 3 billion rupiah from the
state budget for the country's Asian Games team, but then cut it
by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Agung suggested that the council undertake fund-raising
activities itself if it wanted more money.
</P>
<P>
"They can raise public funds, perhaps. I believe the people are
willing to help the national team compete in the Asian Games," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Council's chairman Wismoyo Arismunandar, despite his gratitude,
said the money was not enough. He expected the projected budget to
swell to 7 billion rupiah due to the sharp depreciation of the
rupiah against the U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He plans to hold a meeting with some ministers to find a way to
raise more money.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Minister of Defense/Armed Forces Commander
Gen. Wiranto had agreed to fly the contingent to Bangkok either by
Hercules or Boeing military aircraft. 
</P>
