<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves New Loans To Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved two
loans totaling 700 million U.S. dollars for Thailand's financial
reforms and initiatives to mitigate social impacts of the economic
crisis on the poor and unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The bank announced on Friday that it would increase to 2.2
billion dollars the total aid pledged to Thailand since its
financial crisis erupted a year ago, Saturday's Bangkok Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
The previous pledge was 1.5 billion dollars, part of a 17.2-
billion-dollar package originally brokered by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The report said the aid increase implied that Thailand's
economic recovery was more difficult than expected.
</P>
<P>
"The recession has deepened," said the bank's country director
for Thailand, J. Shivakumar. "There is a need to expand on the
fiscal side, and there is a need to prime the economy a bit. That
was not foreseen last year."
</P>
<P>
The first of the new loans, the 400 million dollars for
economic and financial adjustment, will address the cause of the
crisis and help restructure Thailand's financial and corporate
sectors while strengthening the competitive foundations of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
It will help restore macroeconomic stability and fiscal
balance, implement critical financial sector restructuring and
public enterprise reform, and sharpen competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
As a response to social impacts of the crisis, the second loan,
worth 300 million dollars, will be provided for Thailand's Social
and Investment Project to help protect the poor and unemployed
through employment generation programs and the provision of
essential social services, such as basic health and Aids care.
</P>
<P>
"These loans are an important part of our response to the
crisis," said Shivakumar. "We are committed to working with the
government of Thailand and our partners in the development
community to implement reforms and protect the poor while helping
Thailand return to the path of economic growth." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
