<HEADLINE> Pamana Canal Water Level Back to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Panama Canal Commission
announced Friday that the canal's water level has risen to the
normal 39.5 feet, allowing ships to pass through without
limitations.
</P>
<P>
A deputy director of the commission told a press conference
that the commission has taken every possible measure to raise the
canal water level, which had fallen from the normal 39.5 feet to
35.5 feet on April 28 because of a drought caused by the El Nino
weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The falling water level forced the commission to reduce the
draft of ships passing along the 81-kilometer waterway 22 times in
the 12 months after June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The deputy director said the commission invested 12 million
U.S. dollars to neutralize the impact of the drought by stopping
the use of water in the canal reservoir to generate power, and by
dredging parts of the canal, a short cut for ships passing between
the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
