<HEADLINE> Russian Grain Crops Hit by Widespread Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia is expected to suffer great
crop losses this year because of widespread drought, Viktor
Alexandrovich Semyonov, Russia's minister of agriculture and food,
warned on Friday.
</P>
<P>
This year's grain yield is predicted to be about 64 to 67
million tons, a dramatic drop from last year's 88.5 million tons,
Russia's Interfax news agency quoted Semyonov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Droughts attacked 85 farming areas in Russia, and contributed
dominantly to the anticipated crop losses this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's grain stocks, which amount to 20 million tons, will
make up for the country's domestic food deficiency caused by the
crop failure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Droughts had inflicted a two-billion ruble (319,000
U.S. dollars) loss upon Russia's agriculture-industry complexes,
said Semyonov, who once acted as the first vice-president of the
peasants' and workers' union, and was also president of a large
agriculture company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
