<HEADLINE> Tuxtla Summit To Be Held in El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and the five Central
American countries will hold the third Tuxtla Summit on July 17 in
El Salvador to discuss further cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan press quoted Mexican ambassador to Guatemala
Salvador Arriola as saying that this summit will secure the
"privileged association" promoted by Mexico in Central America.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican diplomat said the Tuxtla Cooperation Mechanism has
set the basis for a new political, economic, social, and cultural
relationship "which has already sustained and now consolidates
itself."
</P>
<P>
Arriola said the regional summit meeting "has facilitated the
cooperation and the political dialogue between Mexico and Central
America."
</P>
<P>
The Tuxtla meetings started as an effort by the Mexican
government to achieve a rapprochement with Central American
countries, after the end of armed conflicts in the region during
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador stressed that the rapprochements had generated
joint tasks of regional benefit in commerce, migration,
environment, health, education and infrastructures, as well as in
combating drug trafficking and international crime.
</P>
<P>
He said relations between Mexico and Guatemala have become
stronger in the Tuxtla agreement context, and permitted the
implementation of 90 activities each year, as well as 30
agreements in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Mexico, El Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala,
Nicaragua and Honduras are expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The first summit meeting was held in 1991 in Tuxtla Gutierrez,
in the southeastern Mexican state of Chiapas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
