<HEADLINE> Belarus Calls EU's Visa Denial Political Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Belarusian Foreign Ministry
said Friday that by threatening to deny Belarusian officials of
entry visas the European Union (EU) was imposing political
pressure on Belarus.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry said all diplomatic envoys
must respect the law of the country where they are accredited,
according to a Russian press report from Minsk, capital of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after a joint written representation
submitted Thursday by the charges d'affaires ad interim of five EU
countries, Britain, Germany, Italy, France and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Addressed to Belarusian Foreign Minister Ivan Antonovich, the
representation said that in response to the Drozdy incident, the
European Union would deny all Belarusian officials of entry visas
to the EU.
</P>
<P>
In late June, Belarus asked foreign diplomatic envoys living in
the Drozdy complex to leave so as to facilitate the overhaul of
the building. The diplomats refused but the Belarusian side
insisted.
</P>
<P>
The row developed as many EU countries recalled their
ambassadors in Minsk. Despite recent compromising signals from the
Belarusian side, the EU move may escalate the dispute. 
</P>
