<HEADLINE> Alozie Runs Year's Fastest Time in 100m Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Glory Alozie highlighted
the international athletics meeting in Salamanca, Spain on Friday
with running the fastest 100 meters hurdles of the year.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Spanish-based Alozie clocked 12.46 seconds,
improving half-a-second from her 1997 best. Russian Tatyana
Reshetnikova took second place in 12.84 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The following wind for the sprints and jumps on Friday was
gusting slightly over the legal limit of two meters-per-second for
much of the evening.
</P>
<P>
It helped Erick Walder of the United States to win the men's
long jump event with a wind-assisted 8.54 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 110m hundles, American Courtney Hawkins beat his
compatriot Allen Johnson, the reigning world and Olympic champion,
to win the title with wind-assisted 13.15 seconds. Britain's Tony
Jarrett finished second in 13.33 and Johnson came third in 13.38.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Maksim Tarasov won the pole vault with 5.80 meters but
fell short with his three attempts at six meters.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Fermin Cacho, 1992 Olympic 1,500m champion and silver
medallist of the 1997 world championship, retired hurt from the
1,500m race. His compatriot Bruno Toledo wrested the title with a
time of three minutes 42.78 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
