<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Insurers Told to Prepare for Oldies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's National Demographic
Society on Friday called on social insurers of the country to make
preparations in advance to meet the challenges of an ageing
population.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the association showed that the average
life expectancy of the population had increased from 36 in 1930 to
74 in 1998. In 1998, there were 4.4 million in the country who
were above the age of 65, accounting for 4.6 percent of the total
population.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2030, the total number of the elderly people in
Mexico would reach 15.6 million, accounting for 12 percent of the
nation's population, and marking an average annual growth of four
percent, the society predicted.
</P>
<P>
Noting that three-fourths of the ageing population would appear
after the year 2020, the society called on Mexicans to get
prepared organizationally and financially to meet the challenges
posed by the ageing population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
