<HEADLINE> Chinese Court Using Polygraph As New Crime Solving Method </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Polygraph results have been
admitted for the first time by Chinese judges and have been called
successful.
</P>
<P>
The Kunming Intermediate People's Court in southwest China's
Yunnan Province introduced the lie detector results in a homicide
case and in one business dispute recently.
</P>
<P>
Court experts concluded in the homicide case that a suspect and
his gay friend were guilty of murder, even though the suspect who
confessed to the crime denied any involvement by his friend.
</P>
<P>
The court's decision was confirmed by a police investigation.
</P>
<P>
In the business dispute over the ownership of an estate, a man
who claimed the estate was his private property failed to pass the
polygraph test.
</P>
<P>
A court spokesman explained that the equipment used by the
court was acquired from the United States and Germany last year,
to improve the ability to solve cases and see that justice is
done, and, "So far, it is successful."
</P>
<P>
The Kunming Intermediate People's Court has become known for
its open-mindedness since it took the lead in using lethal
injections to execute criminals last March.
</P>
<P>
"The court needs to reform some case-handling methods in order
to catch up with international standards," the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
