<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Lobbies Clinton for Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
lobbied United States President Bill Clinton for support Friday
over Russia's bid for a multi-billion dollar bailout package.
</P>
<P>
Russia is holding talks with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the World Bank (WB) on the package.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's press service said that during a trans-Atlantic
telephone call to Clinton, the U.S. president noted the Russian
government's program to stabilize the nation's economy had won
high praise from the international community, and financial
circles.
</P>
<P>
Clinton believed implementation of the program would help
Russia overcome its domestic financial crisis as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents stressed Russian's efforts should be met
with support from international financial organizations, the
Russian presidential press service said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also spoke with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, French
President Jacques Chirac, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
IMF Director-General Michel Camdessus in a series of calls as he
attempted to secure international backing for the package,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The European and IMF leaders expressed support for the
government's anti-crisis package, designed to end a fiscal crisis
which has sent stocks plunging, interest rates spiralling and
threatened the ruble, the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Russia, the IMF and the WB are negotiating and are
trying to hammer out a rescue financial deal for the troubled
Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, presidential special envoy to international
financial institutions, revealed they would make a deal during the
weekend for a 10 to 15 billion U.S. dollar loan to Russia in the
bid to stabilize its financial situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
