<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Review ASEAN Tariff Reduction Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
review a tariff reduction program under the ASEAN Free Trade Area
(AFTA) in light of the lingering financial turmoil hitting the
region, a newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary Jose Pardo was quoted
as saying on Friday that trade ministers from the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are expected to meet this month to
review the region's trade liberalization program.
</P>
<P>
"I presume the interest level on this subject will be high
because it is a common agenda among ASEAN countries," Pardo was
quoted by the Manila Bulletin as saying.
</P>
<P>
AFTA, which calls for a 0-5 percent tariff rate on all
manufactured products traded within the region by the year 2003,
is being implemented via the Common Effective Preferential Tariff
(CEPT) scheme.
</P>
<P>
Pardo, however, said the agreed timetable for the year 2003
will continue but the rate at which the tariff cuts are
implemented may have to be restudied.
</P>
<P>
As the region are stumbling economically due to the financial
crisis, ASEAN countries are expected to slow down their tariff
reduction, although they have to keep the commitment under AFTA to
meet the year 2003 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has rejected calls from the
local business community to freeze tariffs until the year 2003 to
give local industries enough time to recover from the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Local industries have been complaining about the government's
accelerated tariff reduction program, which they said is a lot
faster than any other ASEAN countries'. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
