<HEADLINE> Colombians Support Dialogue With Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The nationwide public
opinion welcomed Thursday's meeting between President-elect Andres
Pastrana and the leaders of the Colombian Revolutionary Armed
Forces of (FARC) Manuel Marulanda Veliz ("Tirofijo") and Jorge
Briseno
</P>
<P>
However, it believes that not much should be expected from the
meeting and that any action must be very cautious.
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Samper said, "it is a very positive step and
if we add to this the dialogue to be started with the National
Liberation Army (ELN), we can say that peace is an irreversible
process."
</P>
<P>
Samper also said that it is necessary to take risks to make
peace and Pastrana did.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is the largest guerrilla organization in Colombia with
4400 supporters, while ELN is the second largest guerrilla group
with about 4000 supporters.
</P>
<P>
Horacio Serpa, the candidate who lost the presidential
election, offered his "full support" for the incoming president's
efforts for peace.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Galan, an ELN spokesman, now a prisoner, called the
meeting of Pastrana with the FARC heads historical.
</P>
<P>
He said that the meeting in Germany with the ELN, as well as
the contacts with the FARC, are complementary processes.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Ardila Lulle, who spoke on behalf of the private sector,
said that "as entrepreneurs and as Colombians we are determined to
contribute to anything that means peace."
</P>
<P>
The Colombian church -- in the voice of Bishop Noel Beltran --
said that "these predialogues will define the future of the
dialogues, without any preconditions and with plans to accelerate
the peace process."
</P>
<P>
However, the commander of the Fifth Division of the Army, Gen.
Jorge Enrique Mora Rangel, considered it necessary to wait before
rushing into any conclusion.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think that the FARC is demonstrating anything; all
the time it has been the same. If a review is made, it will be
seen that there is a constant ambivalence in their acts," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
