<HEADLINE> Costa Rica on Alert for Hemorrhagic Dengue Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Health Minister
Rogelio Pardo announced Friday that emergency measures will be
taken to face up a dengue outbreak in the South Pacific zone,
close to the border with Panama.
</P>
<P>
Seven cases of hemorrhagic dengue have already been detected in
the zone. The disease can kill the patient if adequate medical
attention is not available.
</P>
<P>
The hospital of the zone receives 50 patients a day suffering
from what is called classical dengue, a less serious form of the
disease which causes high fever, headaches and body cramps.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is endemical in the Central American region, but it
broke out with more virulence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The present outbreak is one of the most serious occurred in the
past few months in the country and it could cause the closing of
the tax free zone of El Golfito, located some 180 kilometers from
San Jose, to which a great number of Costa Ricans go to buy
staples.
</P>
<P>
The disease is carried by the Aedes aegypti mosquito, which
transmits the virus to human beings through biting.
</P>
<P>
The health minister said that the number of dengue outbreaks
increases in all the country with the arrival of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
He insisted in the necessity of the population to take measures
to prevent the accumulation of water and reduce the presence of
the mosquito by spraying insecticide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
