<HEADLINE> China's State Televison Beams Alive First Courtroom Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) - China's state-run television
station broadcast alive for the first time a courtroom hearing
across the country at this morning.
</P>
<P>
The broadcast is organized by the Supreme People's Court (SPC)
and is regarded as a major breakthrough in the reforms of China's
legal system as well as media reporting, according to an SPC
official. China Central Television (CCTV) beams the program at
Channel 1.
</P>
<P>
The trial, in Beijing's No.1 Intermediate People's Court,
involves alleged copyright violations of feature films. CCTV has
invited two legal experts on hand to explain to the audience the
proceedings of the hearing while the trial is broadcast alive.
</P>
<P>
The SPC official said that the live broadcast would in no way
interfere with proper legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese law, intermediate court judges can seek
the advice of a higher court or the SPC, but neither the Beijing
Higher People's Court nor the SPC have received a request for
legal assistance so far, the official said. This means that the
trial itself is conducted independently by the Beijing's No.1
Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
SPC officials also said that this live coverage event is the
latest development of China's effort to open its courtrooms to
public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
The SPC says that some 20 local television channels have so far
shown trials or excerpts of trials after cooperating with the
local courts, and that some were live telecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
