<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Make Slim Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street posted slim
gains Friday after some early weakness, but the buying was
hesitant the rolling out of company profit reports.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed 15.96 higher at
9,105.74, slightly more than 100 points from May 13's peak of
9,211.84.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip measure rose 80.48 points for the week, bringing
this year's gain to nearly 1,200 points, or 15.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indexes also turned higher, with the Nasdaq
composite setting a new high for the third straight day. But
declining issues outnumbered advancers overall.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said investors were also hesitant because of Sunday's
elections in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 5.77 to 1,164.33, about 2 points
below Wednesday's closing record of 1,166.38. For the year, the S&AMP;P
500 is up 20.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 3.22 to a
record 1,943.04, extending 1998's gain to 23.7 percent
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 689.50 million
shares, down sharply from 794.86 million on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 1.95 to 592.18, about 2 points
below Wednesday's record of 594.35.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.75 to
730.66, but the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.57
to 458.43.  
</P>
</TEXT>
