<HEADLINE> U.S. Agriculture Department Forecasts Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Record yields in the southern
Plains lifted the U.S. Winter wheat crop up 9 percent from last
month's estimate, the Agriculture Department reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
As of July 1, farmers were expected to harvest 1.9 billion
bushels of Winter wheat. Yields were forecast at a record 46.6
bushels per acre for Winter wheat, due to excellent crops in
Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
Including Spring-planted varieties of wheat, the total U.S.
wheat crop this year is forecast at 2.52 billion bushels or
slightly less than 1997. Overall yields are estimated at 42.6
bushels an acre, also a new record.
</P>
<P>
Early projections for the corn crop placed total production at
9.6 billion bushels, which is lower than the June forecast but
still above 1997's harvest.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department expects this year's ending corn
stocks to increase by 235 million bushels due to reductions in
feed and industrial use.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary soybean projection was raised 30 million
bushels to 2.8 billion bushels, based on a record planted acreage
and good harvest prospects.
</P>
<P>
Because of drought in Texas, the cotton crop is forecast down
1.5 percent to 15 million bales. Rice is expected to top 9.4
million tons, up from about 9.1 million tons last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
