<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysians Urged to Have Faith in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Saturday urged the people to have confidence in
the government in whatever action it takes to tide over the
economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when addressing an all-community gathering
in Malacca, some 145 kilometers southeast of here, according to
Malaysia's national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"The government had no other motives besides defending the
rights of the people. That's only the government's motive.
Whatever action we take, it is for the people," he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia could face the challenges at hand calmly and protect
its sovereignty, he said, adding "The government will try its best
but it needs the people's support. The people's unity is crucial
in our efforts to defend our country's sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he was grateful to be the leader of a country
whose people were matured as they did not resort to riots or
strikes as in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked the trade unions for not creating problems as
the people's purchasing power had dwindled due to soaring prices
of goods and services compared with their salaries.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, however, said the people did not very much feel the
pinch of the economic slowdown but companies faced big problems
and many might go bankrupt. He said banks are under tremendous
pressure and if this continues, the people will suffer.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to be wary against allegations that the
government practiced nepotism and cronyism by awarding projects
and contracts to friends and relatives of government leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "The allegations are not true at all. We must be
careful against such people as they have forked tongue."
</P>
<P>
He also said many people advised him not to talk on the
currency crisis but "if I did not explain to the people, they will
not know the actual situation."
</P>
<P>
"Many of us also want to believe there is irregularities in the
country's administration. If we believe so and spread the news,
confidence in the government will be eroded and the country will
have a weak government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a weak government would not be able to defend the
country's sovereignty from foreigners' attacks.
</P>
<P>
"What they did to us is very cruel indeed. We slogged for 20
years to develop our country but all our hard work was wiped out
in a month," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia had not been compelled to seek assistance from
the International Monetary Fund (IMF). "This is testimony to the
Malaysian government's strength," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
